 borders of India==\n{{anchor| Land }}\n \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Land Border Country\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" |Length (m) and (m)<ref name=\"ejyoti.com\">[http://www.ejyoti.com/facts-about-india/548-list-of-countries-where-india-shares-its-political-borders.htm eJyoti Discovering facts, Information website ]</ref>\n! Force\n! Comments\n|-\n|| {{Flagicon|Bangladesh}} [[Bangladesh\u2013India border|Bangladesh]] || {{convert|4096|km|mi|abbr=}}||[[Border Security Force]] || [[India\u2013Bangladesh enclaves]] exchanged. \n|-\n||{{Flagicon|Bhutan}} [[Bhutan\u2013India border|Bhutan]]||{{convert|699|km|mi|abbr=}}<ref name=\"toi1\">[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/ssb-to-strengthen-presence-on-india-bhutan-border/articleshow/62181663.cms SSB to strengthen presence on India-Bhutan border], Times of India, 20 Dec 2017.</ref>||[[Sashastra Seema Bal]]|| Open border\n|-\n|| {{Flagicon|China}} [[McMahon Line|China]] || {{convert|3488|km|mi|abbr=}}||[[Indo-Tibetan Border Police]] and [[Special Frontier Force]] || Also see [[McMahon Line]].  \n|-\n|| {{Flagicon|Myanmar}} [[India\u2013Myanmar barrier|Myanmar]] || {{convert|1643|km|mi}}  || [[Assam Rifles]] and [[Indian Army]] || \n|-\n|| {{Flagicon|Nepal}} [[Nepal]] || {{convert|1751|km|mi|abbr=}}<ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/ssb-to-strengthen-presence-on-india-bhutan-border/articleshow/62181663.cms</ref>||[[Sashastra Seema Bal]]  || Open border.\n|-\n|| {{Flagicon|Pakistan}} [[India\u2013Pakistan border|Pakistan]] || {{convert|3323|km|mi}}  || [[Border Security Force]] || Also see [[Radcliffe Line]], [[Operation Meghdoot]] and [[Sir Creek]]. \n|- \n|}\n\n== Maritime borders of India ==\n{{anchor| Maritime }}\n\n'''Maritime borders of India''' are the [[maritime boundary]] recognized by the [[United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea]] entails boundaries of [[territorial waters]], [[contiguous zone]]s, and [[exclusive economic zones]]. India, with its claim of a {{convert|12|NM|sing=on}} territorial maritime zone and {{convert|200|NM|sing=on}} exclusive economic zone, has a more than {{convert|7000|km|sing=on}} maritime border shared with seven nations.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Maritime Border Country\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" |Length (km) and (mi)<ref name=\"ejyoti.com\"/>\n! Force\n! Comments\n|-\n|| {{Flagicon|Bangladesh}} [[Bangladesh\u2013India border#Maritime boundary|Bangladesh]] || || [[Indian Navy]] || [[New Moore Island]]\n|-\n|| {{Flagicon|Indonesia}} [[Indonesia]] || || [[Indian Navy]] || [[Indira Point]]\n|-\n|| {{Flagicon|Myanmar}} [[Myanmar]] || || [[Indian Navy]] || [[Coco Islands]]\n|-\n|| {{Flagicon|Pakistan}} [[Pakistan]] || || [[Indian Navy]] || [[Sir Creek]]\n|-\n|| {{Flagicon|Thailand}} [[India\u2013Thailand relations#India-Thailand maritime boundary|Thailand]] || || [[Indian Navy]] || [[Similan Islands]]\n|-\n|| {{Flagicon|Sri Lanka}} [[Sri Lanka]] || >{{convert|400|km|mi}}<ref name=SL1>[https://www.iasgs.com/2017/03/fishing-rights-disputes-india-sri-lanka/ India-Sri Lanka fishing rights dispute]</ref> || [[Indian Navy]] || [[Katchatheevu]]\n|-\n|| {{Flagicon|Maldives}} [[Maldives]] || || [[Indian Navy]] || [[Maliku Kandu]]\n|}\n\n==Designated crossings with ICP & LCS ==\n{{anchor | Designated crossings | ICP | LCS }}\n<!-- Convert these to sortable table with several columns. Source cited is old (Oct 2011) and some LCS have been converted to ICP (insert those with new source/citation) and insert any new LCS with source/citation -->\n\nThe [http://www.mdoner.gov.in/zoomimzgemap/zoom-imagemap.php?map=Look%20East%20Policy map of ICP and LCS].\n\n===Integrated Check Posts (ICP) ===\n{{anchor | ICP }}\n\nIndia has 7 functional ICPs, and plans are underway to upgrade 13 more LCS to ICP, including 7 at borders taking total of border ICP to 14, at the cost of {{INRconvert|3000|c}} (c. Oct 2017).<ref name=icp6/><ref name=icp7/> Designated Integrated Check Posts (ICP), with both customs and immigration facilities are:<ref name=icp1>[http://www.mdoner.gov.in/node/1483 ICP of India]</ref>\n\n====[[Bangladesh\u2013India border|India\u2013Bangladesh border]]====\n{{anchor | Bangladesh }}\n\n* [[Assam]]\n** [[Karimganj district#Sutarkandi international border crossing|Karimganj]]-[[Sylhet District|Golapganj uppozilla]] in Sylhet District of  Bangladesh via [[Karimganj district#Sutarkandi international border crossing|Sutarkandi]] integrated checkpost crossing on [[National Highway 37 (India)|NH37]](India) and Sheola post (Sylhet division, Bangladesh), plan announced c. Oct 2017.<ref name=icp6/>\n* [[Meghalaya]]\n** [[Shillong]]-[[Sylhet]] via [[Dawki#Border-crossing|Dawki ICP]] integrated checkpost crossing (Jaintia Hills, India) and Tambil post (Bangladesh). Dawki ICP foundation stone laid in January 2017 and will become operation in 2018.<ref name=icp5>[https://www.telegraphindia.com/1170125/jsp/northeast/story_132223.jsp Dawki ICP foundation stone laid].</ref>\n* [[Mizoram]]\n** Kawrpuichhuah / Kawarpuchiah / Kawripuichhuah near [[Tlabung]] in [[Lunglei district]], opened in Oct 2017.<ref name=icp6/><ref>[https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/india-opens-two-border-crossing-points-with-myanmar-bangladesh/article9883216.ece India opens two border crossing points with Myanmar, Bangladesh], Business Line.</ref><ref name=clar1/>\n* [[Tripura]]\n** [[Agartala]]-[[Dhaka]] via Agartala integrated checkpost (India) and [[Akhaura Upazila|Akhaura]] checkpost crossing, already functional (c. 2017).<ref name=icp7/>\n** \"[[Belonia, India]] - [[Parshuram Upazila|Parshuram, Bangladesh]] road and rail crossing checkposts\" in [[South Tripura district]] which connect the railway from [[Santirbazar]] in India to [[Feni District|Feni]] in Bangladesh. \n* [[West Bengal]] (clockwise from Kolkatta to north)\n**[[Kolkata]]\u2013[[Dhaka]] via [[Petrapole]] integrated checkpost crossing, already functional (c. 2017).<ref name=icp7>[http://www.dhakatribune.com/world/south-asia/2017/10/18/india-plans-to-construct-7-integrated-check-posts-on-bangladesh-border/ 7 border ICP and total 13 ICP coming up]</ref>\n** [[Barasat|Barasat (India) to Ghojadanga (Bangladesh)]], plan announced c. Oct 2017.<ref name=icp6/><ref name=clar2/>\n** [[Mahadipur]] in [[Malda district]] in [[Malda district|Malda]]-[[Rajshahi]] via [[Malda district#Mahadipur international border crossing|Mahadipur]] crossing, in-principal approval in 2019.<ref name=clar2/><ref name=icp6/>\n** [[Fulbari]], plan announced c. Oct 2017.<ref name=icp6/>\n** [[Hili, Dakshin Dinajpur|Hili]], plan announced c. Oct 2017.<ref name=\"icp6\">[http://indianexpress.com/article/india/centre-plans-13-new-integrated-check-posts-to-encourage-engagement-with-neighbours-4895820/], Indian Express, Oct 2017.</ref>\n** [[Changrabandha railway station]], in-principal approval in 2019.<ref name=clar2>[https://nenow.in/north-east-news/delhi-approves-sutarkandi-integrated-check-post-along-indo-bangla-border.html Delhi approves Sutarkandi integrated check post along Indo-Bangla border], North East News, 7 Jan 2019.</ref>\n\n====[[Bhutan\u2013India border|India-Bhutan border]]====\n{{anchor | Bhutan }}\n\n* [[Jaigaon]] at [[Alipurduar district]] of West Bengal, plan approved c. 2016.<ref name=nep1/>\n\n====[[India\u2013Myanmar barrier|India\u2013Myanmar border]]====\n{{anchor | Myanmar | Burma }}\n\n* [[Moreh, India#Integrated Check Post (ICP) Moreh|Moreh ICP]], already operational.<ref name=icp4/>\n* [[Zochachhuah|Zochawchhuah]] ([[Lawngtlai district]] in India) - Zorinpui (Myanmar) at Indo-Myanmar border on [[Kaladan Multi-Modal Transit Transport Project]] has already been operational since Oct 2017.<ref name=icp4>[https://www.google.com.sg/search?client=firefox-b&dcr=0&ei=lWJCWr3sLcrJvgS0ory4CA&q=zorinpui+lawngtlai+&oq=zorinpui+lawngtlai+&gs_l=psy-ab.3...5050.12763.0.13049.20.20.0.0.0.0.285.2665.0j13j2.15.0....0...1c.1.64.psy-ab..5.10.1914...0j0i67k1j0i131k1j0i10k1j0i13k1.0.d3bPEkKCEM4 India opens two border crossing points with Myanmar, Bangladesh], [[Times of India]], 1 Oct 2o17.</ref><ref name=clar1>[https://tradeandcommerce.mizoram.gov.in/page/12th-five-year-plan.html 12th Five Year Plan]</ref> The 22 km long Lunglei\u2013Tlabung\u2013Kawrpuichhuah road was upgraded in 2014-15 in a [[World Bank]]-funded project to enhance India-Bangladesh border connectivity.<ref>[http://www.worldbank.org/en/news/press-release/2014/06/12/107-million-world-bank-project-to-connect-mizoram-with-bangladesh-and-myanmar-via-roads $107 Million World Bank Project to Connect Mizoram with Bangladesh and Myanmar via Roads], [[World Bank]].</ref> Survey for the Rail line from [[Sairang]] to [[Hmawngbuchhuah]] (1 km north of Zochawchhuah) was completed in August 2017 and it will be constructed in future phase.<ref name=railline1>[http://www.powerupconstruction.com/indias-north-east-opensthe-gateway-to-prosperity/ India's north east opened up], PowerUpConstruction.Com</ref>\n\n====[[India\u2013Nepal relations#Border crossings|India-Nepal border]]====\n{{anchor | Nepal }}\n\n* [[Banbasa]] in [[Champawat district]] of Uttrakhand, in-principle approval in 2019.<ref name=clar2/>\n* [[Bhitamore]]/Bhittamore in [[Sitamarhi district]] of Bihar, in-principle approval in 2019.<ref name=clar2/>\n* [[Jogbani]], Bihar<ref name=nep1>[https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/indo-nepal-and-indo-bhutan-border-to-have-more-integrated-check-posts/articleshow/52964568.cms Indo-Nepal and Indo-Bhutan border to have more ICP], Oct 2016.</ref> \t\n* [[Panitanki]], [[Darjeeling district]] of West Bengal,<ref name=nep1/> in-principal approval in 2019.<ref name=clar2/>\n* [[Raxaul]], Bihar<ref name=nep1/>\n* [[Sonauli#Sonauli India-Nepal border crossing|Sonauli]], Uttar Pradesh{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n* [[Rupaidiha]], Uttar Pradesh<ref name=nep1/>\n* [[Taulihawa]]-[[Siddharthnagar]], Uttar Pradesh<ref name=nep1/>\n\n====[[India\u2013Pakistan border#Border crossings|India\u2013Pakistan border]]====\n{{anchor | Pakistan }}\n{{see also|Transport between India and Pakistan}}\n\n* [[Attari]] at [[Wagah]] in Punjab, already operational (2017) (see [[Samjhauta Express]]).\n* [[Munabao]] in [[Barmer district]] in [[Rajasthan]] (see [[Thar Express]])\n\n===Land Customs Stations (LCS) ===\n{{anchor | LCS }}\n\n====[[Bangladesh\u2013India border|India\u2013Bangladesh border]]====\nDesignated Land Customs Stations (LCS) are (no immigration facilities):<ref name=icp11>[http://www.mdoner.gov.in/sites/default/files/silo2_content/Look%20East%20Policy/RIS%20Border%20Trade%20Report%20-%20final.pdf ICP and LCS]</ref>\n\n* [[Assam]]\n** [[Mankachar]] Land Customs Stations (India) - Rowmari post (Natun Bandar, Rongpur division, Bangladesh)\n** [[Karimganj]] Steamer and Ferry Station (KSFS) (India) - Zakiganj post (Sylhet division, Bangladesh)\n** [[Dhubri district|Guwahati Steamer Ghat]] ([[Dhubri district]], India) -\n** [[Dhubri|Dhubri Steamer Ghat]] (Dhubri district, India) - Rowmati (Maymansingh division, Bangladesh)\n** Assam non-functional LCS are:\n*** [[Mahisasan railway station]] (Karimganj district, India) - Shahbazpur (Sylhet division)\n*** [[Golokganj]] (Dhubri district) - Sonahaat (Rongpur Division)\n*** [[Silchar railway station|Silchar Railway Mail Service]] (India) - independent of border (no border, inland LCS)\n* [[West Bengal]]\n* [[Meghalaya]]\n** [[Baghmara, India|Baghmara]] (South Garo Hills, India) - Bijoyour post (Bangladesh)\n** [[East Khasi Hills district|Bholaganj]] (East Khasi Hills district) - Chatak (Sunamganj division)\n** Borsara Land Customs Stations (West Khasi Hills, India) - Borsara post (Bangladesh)\n** [[West Garo Hills district#Economy|West Garo Hills]] - [[Baksiganj Upazila|Bakshiganj]] via [[West Garo Hills district#Mahendraganj international border crossing|Mahendraganj]] crossing on [[National Highway 217 (India)|NH12]] \n** [[Tura, Meghalaya|Tura]]-[[Nalitabari Upazila|Nalitabari]] via [[Dalu, Meghalaya|Dalu]] crossing on [[National Highway 217 (India)|NH217]] (West Garo Hills, India) and Nakugaon post (Bangladesh)\n** [[West Khasi Hills district|Shellabazar]] (West Khasi Hills district) - Sunamganj(Sylhet division)\n** [[South Garo Hills district|Gasuapara]] (South Garo Hills district)- Karoitol (Mymansing division)\n** Meghalaya non-functional LCS are:\n*** [[Mawsynram|Ryngku]] (East Khasi Hills district) - Kalibari (Sonamganj division)\n*** [[Balat, Meghalaya|Balat]] (East Khasi Hills district) - Dolura (Sylhet division)\n* [[Tripura]]\n** [[Sipahijala district|Srimantapur]] ([[Sipahijala district]]) - Bibir Bazar (Comilla division), became operational in January 2016.<ref name=lcs2>[https://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2016/01/07/tripura-opens-new-land-customs-station-along-bangladesh-border Srimantapur LCS opens]</ref> \n** [[Dhalai district|Dhalaighat]] ([[Dhalai district]]) - Kumarghat (Sunamganj division) \n** [[Khowai]]ghat ([[West Tripura district]]) - Balla (Habiganj division)  \n** [[Manu, Tripura|Manu]] (Dhalai district) - Chatlapur (Sylhet division )\n** [[South Tripura district|Muhurighat]] ([[South Tripura district]]) -  Belonia (Feni division )\n** [[North Tripura district|Old Ragnabazar]] ([[North Tripura district]]) - Betul (Fultali) (Sylhet division)\n* [[Mizoram]]\n** Kawarpuchiah integrated checkpost, opened in Oct 2017 by Prime Minister Narendra Modi.<ref name=pm1>[http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/india-opens-two-border-crossing-points-with-myanmar-bangladesh/article9883216.ece India opens two border crossing points with Myanmar, Bangladesh]</ref>\n** Non-functional LCS in Mizoram:\n*** [[Tlabung|Demagiri]] (Lunglei district) - Rangamati (Sylhet division)\n\n====[[India\u2013Pakistan border#Border crossings|India\u2013Pakistan border]]====\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Longewala]] in [[Jaisalmer district]] of Rajsthan\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Border bazaars and haats==\n{{anchor | markets | market | haats | haat | bazaar | bazaars }}\n<!-- NOTE: Old data/source from June 2011. This section needs updating. Also convert it to a sortable table format with multiple columns to capture location and functional status -->\nThis proposed list of border [[bazaar]]s and [[Haat bazaar|haat]]s is in varying stages of implementation, as suggested by State Governments to the [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]] for setting up Border Haats.<ref name=haat1>[http://www.mdoner.gov.in/node/1485 Border haats of India]</ref>\n\n===[[India\u2013Myanmar barrier|India\u2013Myanmar border]]===\nAs of April 2012, India and Myanmar have approved two locations \u2013 Pangsau Pass, Arunachal Pradesh and Somrai in Ukhrul District.  These are likely to be finalised soon during a forthcoming visit of Hon\u2019ble Prime Minister to Myanmar.<ref name=haat1/>\n\n** [[Arunachal Pradesh]] Border Haats\n** Pangsau Pass (Nampong), Changlang - Pangsau, Kachin Province \t \n** Chingsa (Khimiyang Circle), Changlang - Langhong, Kachin Province\n** Makantong (Khimiyang Circle), Changlang - Ngaimong, Kachin Province\n** Wakka/Pongchao/Lazu - Tirap, Kachin Province\n* [[Manipur]] Border Haats\n*** Kongkan Thana, Ukhrul - Aungci \tSuggested by State Government\n*** New Somtal, Chandel - Thenjen, or Khampat\n*** Behiang, Churachandpur - Khenman, or Chikha\n* [[Mizoram]] Border Haats\n** Hruitezawl, Lawngtlai - Varang\n** Hnahlan, Champhai - Darkhai\n** Vaphai, Champhai - Leilet\n** Chakhang, Saiha - Nviaphia\n* [[Nagaland]] Border Haats\n** Avakhung, Phek - Layshi are 32&nbsp;km from each other \t\n** Pangsha, Tuensang - Lahe/Hkamti District HQ are 60&nbsp;km from each other\n** Chemoho/Longwa, Mon - Lahe \tare 60&nbsp;km from each other\n** Molhe, Phek - Pansat are 10&nbsp;km from each other\n\n=== [[Bangladesh\u2013India border|India\u2013Bangladesh border]]===\n** [[Meghalaya]]\n***  Kalaichar, West Garo Hills \t\n***  Balat, West Khasi Hills\n** [[Mizoram]]\n***  Marpara, Mamit - Longkor \t \n***  Sillsury, Lunglei - Mahmuam \t \n***  Tuipuibari, Mamit - Not provided\n***  Nunsuri, Lunglei - Not provided\n** [[Tripura]]: Decision  on Tripura Haats will be subsequent to the completion of agreement w.r.t. Meghalaya Haats.\n***  Kamalasagar, West Tripura\n***  Boxanagar\n***  Bamutia\n***  Srinagar, South Tripura\n***  Ekimpur\n***  Pal Basti (Raghna), North Tripura\n***  Hiracherra (Kailasahar)\n***  Kamalpur, Dhalai\n\n== In popular media ==\n{{anchor | popular }}\n{{expand section|date=December 2019}}\n\nPradeep Damodaran's book ''\"Borderlands: travels across India's boundaries\" chronicles all land borders of India.<ref name=sl1>[https://scroll.in/article/830499/what-will-you-see-if-you-visit-the-precise-point-where-india-ends-and-sri-lanka-begins What will you see if you visit the precise point where India ends and Sri Lanka begins?], Scroll.in, 1 March 2017.</ref> The [[bollywood]] director [[J. P. Dutta]] has specialised in making [[Hindi language|Hindi]] movies with India's border as key element of the theme, his movies are [[Border (1997 film)]], [[Refugee (2000 film)]], [[LOC: Kargil]], [[Paltan (film)]], etc.<ref name=lineinsand1>Adrian M. Athique, 2010, [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/00856400802441920?scroll=top&needAccess=true&journalCode=csas20 A Line in the Sand: The India\u2013Pakistan Border in the Films of J.P. Dutta], Centre for Critical and Cultural Studies, University of Queensland, Pages 472-499.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{col div|colwidth=22em}}\n; India related\n* [[List of extreme points of India|Extreme points of India]]\n* [[Look East policy (India)#Act East policy|Look East policy]]\n* [[India\u2013Myanmar barrier#Look-East Connectivity|Look-East connectivity]]\n* [[Ministry for Development of North Eastern Region#Northeast India connectivity projects|Northeast India connectivity projects]]\n\n; General\n* [[How Long Is the Coast of Britain?|How different scales of measurement impacts the length of land border]]\n\n; Lists\n* [[List of countries and territories by land borders]]\n* [[List of countries and territories by land and maritime borders]]\n* [[List of countries and territories by maritime boundaries]]\n* [[List of countries that border only one other country]]\n* [[List of land borders by date of establishment]]\n* [[List of divided islands]]\n* [[List of island nations]]\n* [[List of political and geographic borders]]\n{{col div end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last1=Orton |first1=Anna |title=India's Borderland Disputes: China, Pakistan, Bangladesh, and Nepal |date=2010 |publisher=Epitome Books |isbn=9789380297156 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0RBOnS8KsgcC&dq=india%27s+bordering+countries&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.mdoner.gov.in/sites/default/files/silo2_content/Look%20East%20Policy/RIS%20Border%20Trade%20Report%20-%20final.pdf MDoNER Northeast India and SAARC Trade Assessment report]\n* [https://www.un.org/Depts/los/reference_files/chronological_lists_of_ratifications.htm List of countries that have ratified Law of the Sea Conventions]\n{{Borders of India|collapsed}}\n{{Asia topic |Borders of}}\n{{India topics}}\n\n[[Category:Borders of India|*]]\n", "name_user": "182.66.141.149", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(new content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Borders_of_India"}
{"title_page": "1932 San Ciprian hurricane", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Category 4 Atlantic hurricane in 1932}}\n{{Infobox Hurricane\n| Name=1932 San Ciprian hurricane\n| Type=hurricane\n| Year=1932\n| Basin=Atl\n| Image location=San Ciprien Hurricane Analysis 27 Sept 1932.png\n| Image name=[[Surface weather analysis]] of the storm while over [[Puerto Rico]] on September&nbsp;27\n| Image alt=Map plotting the position of the storm and associated isobars, with the center of the storm marked with an \"L\"\n| Formed= {{start date|September 25, 1932}}\n| Dissipated= {{end date|October 2, 1932}}\n| 1-min winds=125\n| Pressure=943\n| Damages=35.6\n| Fatalities=272\n| Areas=[[Virgin Islands]], [[Puerto Rico]], [[Dominican Republic]]\n| Hurricane season=[[1932 Atlantic hurricane season]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1932 San Ciprian hurricane'''{{efn|The Puerto Rican tradition of referring to intense hurricanes by the names of Catholic saints being commemorated on the corresponding [[feast day]]s was among the earliest informal [[tropical cyclone naming]] systems, and lasted for centuries prior to the introduction of standardized naming conventions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tropical Cyclone Naming History and Retired Names|agency=[[National Hurricane Center]]|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|accessdate=April 9, 2020|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/aboutnames_history.shtml}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Yanez, Anthony|date=September 7, 2017|title=From Adrian to Zelda: A History of Hurricane Names|newspaper=[[KNBC|NBC4 Southern California]]|url=https://www.nbclosangeles.com/local/how-hurricanes-get-their-names-storms-weather/23317/|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NWSJetStream\">{{cite web |title=Tropical Cyclone Names |url=https://www.weather.gov/jetstream/tc_names |website=NWS JetStream |publisher=National Weather Service |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> The 1932 San Ciprian hurricane struck Puerto Rico on the feast day of [[Cyprian and Justina|Saint Cyprian]], September&nbsp;26.<ref name=\"PRReport33\">{{cite web |last1=Beverly |first1=James R. |title=Thirty-Third Annual Report of the Governor of Puerto Rico 1933 (Excerpts)|at=Hurricane of 1932 |url=http://newdeal.feri.org/pr/pr12.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010707074924/http://newdeal.feri.org/pr/pr12.htm|archive-date=July 7, 2001 |website=Puerto Rico in the Great Depression |publisher=Government of Puerto Rico|via=Franklin and Eleanor Roosevelt Institute |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |location=San Juan, Puerto Rico |date=July 1, 1933}}</ref> Although the storm is commonly known as ''San Ciprian'', this is a misnomer; the correct translation for Saint Cyprian in Spanish is ''San Cipriano''.<ref name=\"HuracanesPuertoRico\">{{cite web |title=Huracanes y Tormentas Tropicales Que Han Afectado a Puerto Rico |url=http://www.gobierno.pr/NR/rdonlyres/49EA64D0-305B-4881-8B85-04B518004BD5/0/Ciclones_en_PR.pdf |publisher=Agencia Estatal de Puerto Rico para la Gesti\u00f3n de Emergencias y Administraci\u00f3n de Desastres |accessdate=April 14, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090612054045/http://www.gobierno.pr/NR/rdonlyres/49EA64D0-305B-4881-8B85-04B518004BD5/0/Ciclones_en_PR.pdf |archivedate=June 12, 2009 |location=San Juan, Puerto Rico |pages=12\u201313}}</ref>}} was one of the strongest [[tropical cyclone]]s in the [[history of Puerto Rico]]. The center of the storm traversed the island on an east-to-west path in late September&nbsp;1937, killing 225&nbsp;people and inflicting $30&nbsp;million in damage.{{efn|All monetary values are in 1932&nbsp;[[United States dollars]] unless otherwise indicated.|group=nb|name=note-money}} Winds in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], were estimated to have reached at least 120&nbsp;mph (195&nbsp;km/h), causing extensive destruction. The storm's origins can be traced back to at least September&nbsp;25, 1932, when it was a [[tropical storm]] east of the [[Windward Islands]]. Moving west as a compact tropical cyclone, it [[rapid intensification|rapidly intensified]] as it moved across the [[Virgin Islands]] the following day before ultimately making [[landfall (meteorology)|landfall]] on September&nbsp;27 in [[Ceiba, Puerto Rico]], at a peak intensity equivalent to that of a [[List of Category 4 Atlantic hurricanes|Category&nbsp;4 hurricane]] on the modern [[Saffir\u2013Simpson scale]]. The hurricane diminished for the remainder of its duration, egressing Puerto Rico and brushing the southern coast of [[Hispaniola]]. The weakened cyclone passed near [[Jamaica]] on September&nbsp;29 and moved ashore [[British Honduras]] on October&nbsp;1 as a low-end tropical storm, dissipating the next day over southeastern [[Mexico]].\n\nThe San Ciprian Hurricane took an unusual east to west path across [[Puerto Rico]], producing damage across the entire length of the [[United States territory]]. The next storm to follow a similar path was [[Hurricane Georges]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|author=Shawn P. Bennett and Rafael Mojica|year=1998|title=Hurricane Georges Preliminary Storm Report|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=2007-04-12|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/sju/public_report.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014181517/http://www.srh.noaa.gov/sju/public_report.html|archivedate=2008-10-14}}</ref> Overall damage in [[Puerto Rico]] was catastrophic as the storm left $30&nbsp;million (1932&nbsp;USD, equivalent to ${{Inflation|US-GDP|0.03|1932|r=1}}&nbsp;billion in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}}) and 225\u2013257 fatalities. The hurricane also caused moderate damage in the [[Virgin Islands]].<ref name=\"mwr\">{{cite web|author=W.J. Humphreys|year=1932|title=1932 Monthly Weather Review|publisher=NOAA|accessdate=2007-04-12|url=http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/rescue/mwr/060/mwr-060-09-0177.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Meteorological history==\n{{storm path|1932 Atlantic hurricane 9 track.png|alt=A map of the Caribbean Sea showing the path of the hurricane from beginning east of the Leeward Islands and terminating over Central America}}\nThe presence of unusually [[high pressure area|high air pressures]] throughout the Atlantic and eastern North America caused the 1932 San Ciprian hurricane to take an atypical path directed towards the west and west-southwest over its duration.<ref name=\"MWR\">{{cite journal |editor1-last=Humphreys |editor1-first=W. J. |title=West Indian Hurricanes of August and September, 1932 |journal=Monthly Weather Review |date=September 1932 |volume=60 |issue=9 |pages=178\u2013179|doi=10.1175/1520-0493(1932)60<177:TTSOAI>2.0.CO;2 |url=ftp://ftp.library.noaa.gov/docs.lib/htdocs/rescue/mwr/060/mwr-060-09-0177.pdf|via=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |publisher=United States Weather Bureau |location=San Juan, Puerto Rico |format=PDF}}</ref> Details about the hurricane's [[tropical cyclogenesis|genesis]] are unclear due to a lack of contemporaneous weather observations. In 2012, the [[Atlantic hurricane reanalysis|Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory]] (AOML) investigated the storm's history,{{efn|The AOML, through its Hurricane Research Division, [[Atlantic hurricane reanalysis|analyzed]] the system in 2012 as part of a project to reevaluate the [[HURDAT|official hurricane database]] maintained by the [[National Hurricane Center]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Landsea |first1=Christopher W. |last2=Hagen |first2=Andrew |last3=Bredemeyer |first3=William |last4=Carrasco |first4=Cristina |last5=Glenn |first5=David A. |last6=Santiago |first6=Adrian |last7=Strahan-Sakoskie |first7=Donna |last8=Dickinson |first8=Michael |title=A Reanalysis of the 1931\u201343 Atlantic Hurricane Database |journal=Journal of Climate |date=August 2014 |volume=27 |issue=16 |pages=6093\u20136118 |doi=10.1175/JCLI-D-13-00503.1 |url=https://journals.ametsoc.org/doi/pdf/10.1175/JCLI-D-13-00503.1 |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |publisher=American Meteorological Society |location=Boston, Massachusetts |format=PDF}}</ref><ref name=\"Metadata\" /><ref name=\"RAP\">{{cite web |title=Re-Analysis Project |url=https://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/data_sub/re_anal.html |website=Hurricane Research Division |publisher=Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |location=Miami, Florida |date=December 2019}}</ref> Their assessment of the 1932 San Ciprian hurricane made alterations to the storm's track and intensity; for instance, the storm's intensity at its Puerto Rico landfall was originally listed as equivalent to a Category&nbsp;2 hurricane.<ref name=\"Metadata\" />|group=nb}} determining that the hurricane's progenitor had developed into a [[tropical storm]] with [[maximum sustained wind|sustained winds]] of 60&nbsp;mph (95&nbsp;km/h) by 06:00&nbsp;[[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]] on September&nbsp;25, 1932.<ref name=\"Metadata\">{{cite web|last1=Landsea|first1=Chris|last2=Anderson|first2=Craig|last3=Bredemeyer|first3=William|last4=Carrasco|first4=Cristina|last5=Charles|first5=Noel|last6=Chenoweth|first6=Michael|last7=Clark|first7=Gil|last8=Delgado|first8=Sandy|last9=Dunion|first9=Jason|last10=Ellis|first10=Ryan|last11=Fernandez-Partagas|first11=Jose|last12=Feuer|first12=Steve|last13=Gamanche|first13=John|last14=Glenn|first14=David|last15=Hagen|first15=Andrew|last16=Hufstetler|first16=Lyle|last17=Mock|first17=Cary|last18=Neumann|first18=Charlie|last19=Perez Suarez|first19=Ramon|last20=Prieto|first20=Ricardo|last21=Sanchez-Sesma|first21=Jorge|last22=Santiago|first22=Adrian|last23=Sims|first23=Jamese|last24=Thomas|first24=Donna|last25=Lenworth|first25=Woolcock|last26=Zimmer|first26=Mark|authorlink1=Christopher Landsea|title=Documentation of Atlantic Tropical Cyclones Changes in HURDAT|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/metadata_master.html|website=[[Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory]]|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|accessdate=March 23, 2020|date=May 2015|location=[[Miami, Florida]]|type=Metadata|at=1932 Storm #9 - 2012 Revision}}</ref> At that point, the storm was amid a period of intensification and centered approximately 340&nbsp;mi (550&nbsp;km) east of [[Antigua]]. Its winds increased as it moved west, reaching [[hurricane-force]] by 12:00&nbsp;UTC on September&nbsp;25.<ref name=\"IBTrACS\">{{cite web |title=1932 Major Hurricane NOT_NAMED (1932269N17303)|url=http://www.atms.unca.edu/ibtracs/ibtracs_v04r00/index.php?name=v04r00-1932269N17303 |website=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship (IBTrACS) |publisher=[[University of North Carolina at Asheville]] |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |location=[[Asheville, North Carolina]]}}</ref> Early the next day, the hurricane passed near Antigua and [[Saint Barthelemy]], and later between [[Saint Thomas]]{{dn|date=April 2020}} and [[Saint Croix]], tracking west-northwest at roughly 10&nbsp;mph (15&nbsp;km/h).<ref name=\"MWR\" /> Around 13:00&nbsp;UTC on September&nbsp;26, the center of the storm passed near [[Saba]] with winds of 140&nbsp;mph (220&nbsp;km/h);{{efn|[[HURDAT]], the official database for the intensities and tracks of Atlantic tropical cyclones,<ref name=\"RevisedHURDAT\">{{cite web |last1=Landsea |first1=Chris |last2=Franklin |first2=James |last3=Beven |first3=Jack |title=The revised Atlantic hurricane database (HURDAT2) |url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/data/hurdat/hurdat2-format-atlantic.pdf |publisher=National Hurricane Center |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |location=Miami, Florida |format=PDF |date=May 2015}}</ref> lists the maximum sustained winds of storms to the nearest five [[knot (unit)|knots]].<ref name=\"AOMLHURDATGuide\">{{cite web |title=Original HURDAT Format |url=https://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/data_sub/hurdat.html |website=Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory |publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |location=Miami, Florida}}</ref> Conversions to miles per hour (mph) and kilometers per hours (km/h) for values drawn from this database are derived from the original value in knots and rounded to the nearest five.|name=note-hurdat|group=nb}} the steep [[pressure gradient]] measured on that island was indicative of a small and [[rapid intensification|rapidly intensifying hurricane]].<ref name=\"Metadata\" />\n\nAt around 04:00&nbsp;UTC on September&nbsp;27, the compact hurricane made [[landfall (meteorology)|landfall]] on [[Puerto Rico]] near [[Ensenada Honda (Ceiba, Puerto Rico)|Ensenada Honda]] in the municipality of [[Ceiba, Puerto Rico|Ceiba]]. Upon moving ashore, the hurricane had sustained winds estimated at 145&nbsp;mph (230&nbsp;km/h){{efn|name=note-hurdat}} and a minimum central pressure of 943&nbsp;[[bar (unit)|mbar]] ([[pascal (unit)|hPa]]; 27.85&nbsp;[[inches of mercury|inHg]]), equivalent to a [[List of Category 4 Atlantic hurricanes|Category 4 hurricane]] on the modern [[Saffir\u2013Simpson scale]]. The region of hurricane-force winds was likely no larger than 23&nbsp;mi (37&nbsp;km) in diameter upon landfall, with a [[radius of maximum wind]]s likely smaller than 12&nbsp;mi (19&nbsp;km). The storm's center tracked over Puerto Rico for seven hours on an east-to-west course before emerging into the [[Caribbean Sea]] off [[Aguadilla, Puerto Rico|Aguadilla]].<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> Land interaction with Puerto Rico caused the storm's maximum winds to decrease to 105&nbsp;mph (165&nbsp;km/h);{{efn|name=note-hurdat}} the hurricane maintained this strength until it struck the southern ends of the [[Dominican Republic]] and [[Haiti]] on September&nbsp;28.<ref name=\"MWR\" /><ref name=\"Metadata\" /><ref name=\"IBTrACS\" /> This second landfall weakened the system significantly, reducing the winds to 45&nbsp;mph (75&nbsp;km/h).{{efn|name=note-hurdat}}<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> The storm took a slightly south of west heading for the rest of its duration, passing near [[Jamaica]] on September&nbsp;29.<ref name=\"IBTrACS\" /> According to the AOML, the storm might have weakened to a [[tropical depression]] between September&nbsp;29\u201330 while traversing the western Caribbean.<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> The tropical storm reorganized slightly upon making its final landfall south of [[Belize City]] in [[British Honduras]] at around 18:00&nbsp;UTC on October&nbsp;1 with winds of 45&nbsp;mph (75&nbsp;km/h).{{efn|name=note-hurdat}} It progressed west-southwest into southeastern [[Mexico]], weakening before dissipating on October&nbsp;2.<ref name=\"Metadata\" />\n\n{{clear}}\n==Preparations==\nThe [[Weather Bureau|United States Weather Bureau]] office in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]] was first made aware of the storm's presence on September&nbsp;26, following a report of the passage of a \"moderate disturbance\" near Antigua.<ref name=\"MWR\" />  Its first storm bulletin was issued that evening after the center of the storm passed between Saint Thomas and Saint Croix, noting the rapidity of the storm's movement and its small size.<ref name=\"MWR\" /><ref name=\"MayStrikeSection\">{{cite news |title=Hurricane May Strike Section of Puerto Rico |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34065415/|via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=The News-Herald |agency=United Press |issue=16046 |date=September 26, 1932 |location=Franklin, Pennsylvania |page=1}}</ref> This and subsequent bulletins were disseminated in Puerto Rico by the [[Government of Puerto Rico|territorial government]], the [[U.S. Navy]], and local radio station [[WKAQ (AM)|WKAQ]]. The San Juan Weather Bureau office lauded these bodies in their report on the storm published in the ''[[Monthly Weather Review]]'', writing that \"the loss of life and property damaged were materially reduced\" due to their efforts.<ref name=\"MWR\" /> There were 18&nbsp;hours of advance warning for San Juan before the hurricane struck.<ref name=\"WestIndianHurricanes\">{{cite journal |last1=Cook |first1=Melville T. |title=West Indian Hurricanes |journal=The Scientific Monthly |date=1933 |volume=37 |issue=4 |pages=307\u2013315 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/15604 |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |issn=0096-3771}}</ref> The bureau continued to issue advisories concerning the storm twice daily through October&nbsp;1.<ref name=\"MWR\" />\n\nAt the beginning of the [[1932 Atlantic hurricane season]], the [[Governor of Puerto Rico]], [[James R. Beverly]], directed mayors in the territory to organize municipal emergency committees, requiring each to hoist hurricane [[flag signals]] at the cathedrals and city halls of every town whenever a hurricane warning was in effect. Mayors and police forces in Puerto were advised by the Weather Bureau's first statements on the storm to begin safeguarding lives and property. A meeting was held on the afternoon of September&nbsp;26 between the governor, heads of executive departments, the manager of the Puerto Rican chapter of the [[American Red Cross]], and other prominent citizens to formulate plans of actions for possible emergencies arising from the hurricane's passage; these included the mobilization of crews to repair communications infrastructure and police-assisted evacuation of vulnerable people into the sturdiest buildings.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> The American Red Cross in the continental U.S. also prepared to send aid to Puerto Rico when necessary.<ref name=\"RedCrossPreparesSendAid\">{{cite news |title=Red Cross Prepares to Send Aid to Puerto Rico |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48435866/|via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The News-Herald |agency=United Press |issue=16047 |date=September 27, 1932 |location=Franklin, Pennsylvania|page=1}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Dominican Republic]], the hurricane's approach triggered fears of a second disaster as that country was still recovering from the destruction by the [[1930 Dominican Republic Hurricane]] two years earlier.<ref name=\"sdh\">{{cite web|author=Syracuse Herald|year=1932|title=San Domingo and Haiti in the storms path|accessdate=2007-04-18|url=http://www.thehurricanearchive.com/Viewer.aspx?img=51364509&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=0&currentPage=0|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921000811/http://www.thehurricanearchive.com/Viewer.aspx?img=51364509&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=0&currentPage=0|archive-date=2017-09-21|url-status=dead}}</ref> The concern prompted residents to close businesses and evacuate; some sought to nearby churches for shelter.<ref name=\"tvm\">{{cite web|author=United Press|year=1932|title=Long Trail of death and damage left by the storm|publisher=The Vidette-Messenger|accessdate=2007-04-18|url=http://www.thehurricanearchive.com/Viewer.aspx?img=56650985&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=0&currentPage=10}}{{Dead link|date=February 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In [[Jamaica]], meteorologists forecast the storm to move north of the island after passing over [[Port-au-Prince]], [[Haiti]]. The track of the storm prompted the forecasters to issue advisories for oceangoing [[ships]] and small watercraft.<ref name=\"tglen\">{{cite web|author=The Daily Gleaner|year=1932|title=Jamaica in the danger zone|accessdate=2007-04-19|url=http://www.thehurricanearchive.com/Viewer.aspx?img=17604907&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=0&currentPage=0}}{{Dead link|date=February 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The countries of [[Honduras]] and [[Belize]] also took preparations ahead of the storm as people closed shops and other businesses in anticipation of the storm's landfall.<ref>{{cite web|author=Associated Press|year=1932|title=Honduras shops close as hurricane nears|publisher=The Syracuse Herald|accessdate=2007-04-19|url=http://www.thehurricanearchive.com/Viewer.aspx?img=23989821&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=0&currentPage=0}}{{Dead link|date=February 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n[[File:Hurrpaths.JPG|thumb|300px|The tracks of three Puerto Rican hurricanes, including the 1932&nbsp;storm|alt=Map of three hurricane tracks across Puerto Rico and the Greater Antilles]]\n===Virgin Islands===\nThe hurricane's small size was evidenced by wind observations at Saint Thomas and Saint Croix, which are located roughly 45&nbsp;mi (75&nbsp;km) apart. Despite the center of the hurricane passing between the islands, neither island experienced hurricane-force winds, their speeds only reaching 60&nbsp;mph (95&nbsp;km/h).<ref name=\"Metadata\" /><ref name=\"MWR\" /> Moderate damage occurred on Saint Barth\u00e9lemy, [[Saint John, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint John]], Saint Thomas, and [[Tortola]]. Estimated winds of 60\u201390&nbsp;mph (95\u2013145&nbsp;km/h) swept across Saint Barthelemy.<ref name=\"MWR\" /> Radio antennas were blown down by the winds in Saba.<ref name=\"MWR\" /> The firing of warning guns on Saint Thomas 90&nbsp;minutes before the storm's arrival allowed the island's populace to seek shelter. Many houses were damaged and wires and trees were blown down on the island. Small ships capsized in the Saint Thomas harbor. Legislative elections were postponed due to the inclement conditions. Another two passenger-filled [[sloop]]s in Tortola were lost.<ref name=\"VirginIslandsAreStruckByStorm\">{{cite news |title=Virgin Islands Are Struck by Tropical Storm |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48436384/|via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The News-Herald |agency=United Press |issue=16047 |date=September 27, 1932 |location=Franklin, Pennsylvania|page=1}}</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that the hurricane killed 15 people in the [[Virgin Islands]].<ref>{{cite news|author=New York Times|title=SAN JUAN DAMAGED BADLY|accessdate=2007-04-25|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/09/28/archives/san-juan-damaged-badly-120mile-wind-levels-towns-drives-ships.html | work=The New York Times | date=1932-09-28}}</ref>\n\n===Puerto Rico===\nForty-nine [[municipalities of Puerto Rico]] were affected by the storm to varying degrees, with devastation wrought across the northern half of the territory.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> The hurricane's effects killed 257&nbsp;people;<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> most of these fatalities were due to the collapse of buildings, with wind-blown debris and drownings also responsible for some deaths.<ref name=\"MWR\" /> Over 4,820&nbsp;others were injured.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> Though people took shelter in buildings thought to be safe, only well-built masonry and concrete structures withstood the storm in the hardest-hit areas. Concrete buildings made of concrete with a [[properties of concrete|water-to-cement ratio]] and improperly or poorly anchored roofs were destroyed, killing many. Homes with corrugated iron sheet roofs attached using smooth or twisted nails, common in San Juan, were unroofed.<ref name=\"MWR\" /> In total, 45,554&nbsp;houses were razed and another 47,876&nbsp;were partially destroyed.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> The severity of the damage was equivalent to that of an F3&nbsp;tornado on the [[Fujita scale]].<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> Writing to the [[United States Secretary of War]] in 1933, Beverly described the damage was more severe than the [[1928 Okeechobee hurricane|1928 San Felipe hurricane]] for the areas affected.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> Nearly 500,000&nbsp;animals were also killed, including cows, goats, horses, pigs, and poultry.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" />\n\nThe steamships ''Jean'' and ''Acacia'' took refuge at Ensenada Honda, where the hurricane made landfall. Both ships were [[ship grounding|grounded]] by the storm but were refloated after unloading cargo. Several pier buildings at the [[Port of San Juan]]  sustained heavy damage. The three-masted [[schooner]] ''Gaviota'' was wrecked in the harbor. The [[bridge (nautical)|bridge]] and [[ship's boat]]s of another vessel in the harbor were blown away.<ref name=\"MWR\" /> Many smaller ships along the waterfront were driven aground.<ref name=\"PlacedAt200\" /> Telephone and telegraph lines between [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]] and the eastern parts of Puerto Rico were disrupted on the night of September&nbsp;26. The worst of the storm reached San Juan shortly after midnight on the morning of September&nbsp;27 and lasted for about three hours;<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> hurricane-force winds lasted for six hours.<ref name=\"WestIndianHurricanes\" /> Winds of at least 120&nbsp;mph (195&nbsp;km/h) occurred in San Juan, though the local [[measurement tower]] measured a peak wind of 66&nbsp;mph (106&nbsp;km/h) before it was toppled by the storm.<ref name=\"MWR\" /> In San Juan, [[Hato Rey]], and [[R\u00edo Piedras, Puerto Rico|R\u00edo Piedras]], hundreds of homes were blown away and trees were uprooted. The carnage littered streets with debris.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> All communication and electric poles and wires were knocked down.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> WKAQ's [[Radio masts and towers|radio towers]] lay toppled and contorted by the wind.<ref name=\"PlacedAt200\">{{cite news |title=Storm's Dead Placed at 200 in Puerto Rico |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48736951/|via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 14, 2020 |work=The Miami Herald |agency=Associated Press |issue=301|volume=22 |location=Miami, Florida |page=1}}</ref>\n\nReports indicated that all homes collapsed in [[Fajardo, Puerto Rico|Fajardo]] and [[Toa Alta, Puerto Rico|Toa Alta]]. Many small towns outside of the San Juan area were left in similar circumstances.<ref name=\"HurricaneLeavesHeavyDeath\">{{cite news |last1=Beverley |first1=James R. |title=Hurricane Leaves Heavy Death Toll in Antilles Islands |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48736440/|via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 14, 2020 |work=The Napa Journal |agency=United Press |issue=231|volume=79 |date=August 28, 1932 |location=Napa, California|page=1}}</ref>\n\nRainfall totals in Puerto Rico were lower overall than in other hurricanes of similar strength. The maximum total of {{cvt|16.70|in|mm}} was measured in [[Maricao, Puerto Rico|Maricao]].<ref name=\"MWR\" />  Damage to both property and crops amounted to $35.6&nbsp;million, with $15.6&nbsp;million inflicted upon property and $20&nbsp;million inflicted upon crops. The Puerto Rican Department of Commerce that the damage parlayed into $31.2&nbsp;million in economic losses for agriculture.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> The main [[citrus]]-producing regions of Puerto Rico were located within the swath of the heaviest damage; its losses accounted for the largest proportion of crop losses. Though the main coffee tree plantations did not experience the storm's strongest winds, they were heavily damaged by fallen banana trees; banana trees had been planted to provide temporary shading for the new coffee crop following the 1928 San Felipe hurricane but were susceptible to moderate winds. The toll inflicted on citrus and coffee trees delayed their harvests by several years. The hurricane rendered other crops a total loss, though to an extent recoverable within a [[growing season]].<ref name=\"MWR\" /> Approximately $2.4&nbsp;million worth of agricultural plantations and structures constructed using recovery funds from the 1928&nbsp;hurricane were destroyed.<ref name=\"PRC\" /> Forests along the [[Sierra de Luquillo]] were defoliated and exhibited high tree mortality after being lashed by the heavy rains and strong winds.<ref name=\"ARainforestChronicle\">{{cite journal |last1=Crow |first1=Thomas R. |title=A Rainforest Chronicle: A 30-Year Record of Change in Structure and Composition at El Verde, Puerto Rico |journal=Biotropica |date=March 1980 |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=42 |doi=10.2307/2387772}}</ref> East of the Puerto Rican mainland, [[Culebra, Puerto Rico|Culebra]] and [[Vieques]] also sustained heavy damage.<ref name=\"MWR\" /> \n\n===Dominican Republic===\nIn the [[Dominican Republic]], the hurricane produced 90&nbsp;mph (145&nbsp;km/h) winds in [[San Pedro de Macor\u00eds]] and 50&nbsp;mph (80&nbsp;km/h) winds in [[Santo Domingo]].<ref name=\"MWR\" /> Many houses in the interior villages were unroofed.<ref name=\"PuertoRicoWorstSufferer\">{{cite news |title=Puerto Rico Worst Sufferer in Tropic Storm |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48736713/|via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 14, 2020 |work=The Napa Journal |agency=United Press |issue=231|volume=79 |date=August 28, 1932 |location=Napa, California|page=1}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nIn the [[Virgin Islands]], officials and the [[Red Cross]] provided $25,000&nbsp;dollars (1932&nbsp;USD) in relief aid.<ref>{{cite web|author=Associated Press|year=1932|title=Newspaper Report on the Hurricane|publisher=Galveston Daily News|accessdate=2007-04-25|url=http://www.thehurricanearchive.com/Viewer.aspx?img=45206887&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=0&currentPage=0}}{{Dead link|date=February 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nWorkers from the Puerto Rican Department of the Interior, assisted by prisoners and volunteers, quickly cleared roads of debris once the storm passed. [[United States National Guard|National Guard]] and Red Cross personnel were promptly dispatched into the affected areas to aid recovery efforts; medical and food supplies were distributed in the larger impacted municipalities within 24&nbsp;hours of the storm's passage.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> Some of the relief efforts were also managed by the Puerto Rican Hurricane Relief Commission that was formed in response to the 1928&nbsp;hurricane.<ref name=\"PRC\">{{cite report|title=Fourth Annual Report of the Puerto Rican Hurricane Relief Commission |date=December 2, 1932 |publisher=Puerto Rican Hurricane Relief Commission |pages=1\u20136}}</ref> For the 1932&nbsp;storm, a Hurricane Relief and Rehabilitation Commission was formed on September&nbsp;27 in cooperation with the Red Cross, split into an executive committee and two subcommittees. One subcommittee was tasked with enforcing [[price control]]s while the other was tasked with raising relief funds for immediate purchases of materials and to supplement the Red Cross's efforts; nearly $75,000 was collected by this second committee. The funds augmented an emergency fund established by the Puerto Rican government in April&nbsp;1932; $165,000 in relief was sourced from this fund, including a $50,000 loan to the Fruit Growers Cooperative Credit Association for the recovery of the citrus crop and acqusition of fertilizer. Food and shelter relief was administered by the Red Cross. Additional supplies were made available to these committees by the American military stationed in Puerto Rico. Two reconnaissance flights were arranged on September&nbsp;27 and September&nbsp;28 to better determine the extent and severity of the damage across northern Puerto Rico. Teachers were enlisted by the Department of Education to appraise the total property damage while while crop damage was tallied by the Commissioner of Agriculture and Commerce. The Red Cross reported that 76,925&nbsp;families were in \"actual distress\" due to the hurricane.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> The destruction of homes rendered 25,000&nbsp;families homeless.<ref name=\"Rodriguez\">{{cite journal |last1=Rodr\u00edguez |first1=Havid\u00e1n |title=A Socioeconomic Analysis of Hurricanes in Puerto Rico: An Overview of Disaster Mitigation and Preparedness |journal=Hurricanes: Climate and Socioeconomic Impacts |date=1997 |pages=121\u2013143 |doi=10.1007/978-3-642-60672-4_7 |publisher=Springer}}</ref> Total economic losses from the storm were equivalent to 20&nbsp;percent of Puerto Rico's [[gross national income|gross income]].<ref name=\"Sotomayor\">{{cite journal |last1=Sotomayor |first1=Orlando |title=Fetal and infant origins of diabetes and ill health: Evidence from Puerto Rico's 1928 and 1932 hurricanes |journal=Economics & Human Biology |date=July 2013 |volume=11 |issue=3 |pages=281\u2013293 |doi=10.1016/j.ehb.2012.02.009 |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones|Puerto Rico}}\n*[[1867 San Narciso hurricane]]&nbsp;\u2013 \n*[[1876 San Felipe hurricane]]&nbsp;\u2013 \n*[[Hurricane Georges]]&nbsp;\u2013 the first hurricane after 1932 to take an east-to-west path across Puerto Rico<ref name=\"SJUGeorges\">{{cite web |last1=Bennett |first1=Shawn P. |last2=Mojica |first2=Rafael |title=Hurricane Georges Preliminary Storm Report |url=https://www.weather.gov/sju/1998_georges |website=National Weather Service San Juan, Puerto Rico |publisher=National Weather Service |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |location=San Juan, Puerto Rico}}</ref>\n*[[Hurricane Maria]]&nbsp;\u2013 the first storm after 1932 to strike Puerto Rico with at least Category&nbsp;4 hurricane winds<ref name=\"MariaReliefEffort\">{{cite news |last1=Meyer |first1=Robinson |title=What's Happening With the Relief Effort in Puerto Rico? |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2017/10/what-happened-in-puerto-rico-a-timeline-of-hurricane-maria/541956/ |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |work=The Atlantic |date=October 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{1932 Atlantic hurricane season buttons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1932 San Ciprian}}\n[[Category:1932 Atlantic hurricane season|San Ciprian]]\n[[Category:Category 4 Atlantic hurricanes]]\n[[Category:1932 natural disasters|San Ciprian Hurricane]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in Puerto Rico]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Category 4 Atlantic hurricane in 1932}}\n{{Infobox Hurricane\n| Name=1932 San Ciprian hurricane\n| Type=hurricane\n| Year=1932\n| Basin=Atl\n| Image location=San Ciprien Hurricane Analysis 27 Sept 1932.png\n| Image name=[[Surface weather analysis]] of the storm while over [[Puerto Rico]] on September&nbsp;27\n| Image alt=Map plotting the position of the storm and associated isobars, with the center of the storm marked with an \"L\"\n| Formed= {{start date|September 25, 1932}}\n| Dissipated= {{end date|October 2, 1932}}\n| 1-min winds=125\n| Pressure=943\n| Damages=35.6\n| Fatalities=272\n| Areas=[[Virgin Islands]], [[Puerto Rico]], [[Dominican Republic]]\n| Hurricane season=[[1932 Atlantic hurricane season]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1932 San Ciprian hurricane'''{{efn|The Puerto Rican tradition of referring to intense hurricanes by the names of Catholic saints being commemorated on the corresponding [[feast day]]s was among the earliest informal [[tropical cyclone naming]] systems, and lasted for centuries prior to the introduction of standardized naming conventions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tropical Cyclone Naming History and Retired Names|agency=[[National Hurricane Center]]|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|accessdate=April 9, 2020|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/aboutnames_history.shtml}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Yanez, Anthony|date=September 7, 2017|title=From Adrian to Zelda: A History of Hurricane Names|newspaper=[[KNBC|NBC4 Southern California]]|url=https://www.nbclosangeles.com/local/how-hurricanes-get-their-names-storms-weather/23317/|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NWSJetStream\">{{cite web |title=Tropical Cyclone Names |url=https://www.weather.gov/jetstream/tc_names |website=NWS JetStream |publisher=National Weather Service |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> The 1932 San Ciprian hurricane struck Puerto Rico on the feast day of [[Cyprian and Justina|Saint Cyprian]], September&nbsp;26.<ref name=\"PRReport33\">{{cite web |last1=Beverly |first1=James R. |title=Thirty-Third Annual Report of the Governor of Puerto Rico 1933 (Excerpts)|at=Hurricane of 1932 |url=http://newdeal.feri.org/pr/pr12.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010707074924/http://newdeal.feri.org/pr/pr12.htm|archive-date=July 7, 2001 |website=Puerto Rico in the Great Depression |publisher=Government of Puerto Rico|via=Franklin and Eleanor Roosevelt Institute |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |location=San Juan, Puerto Rico |date=July 1, 1933}}</ref> Although the storm is commonly known as ''San Ciprian'', this is a misnomer; the correct translation for Saint Cyprian in Spanish is ''San Cipriano''.<ref name=\"HuracanesPuertoRico\">{{cite web |title=Huracanes y Tormentas Tropicales Que Han Afectado a Puerto Rico |url=http://www.gobierno.pr/NR/rdonlyres/49EA64D0-305B-4881-8B85-04B518004BD5/0/Ciclones_en_PR.pdf |publisher=Agencia Estatal de Puerto Rico para la Gesti\u00f3n de Emergencias y Administraci\u00f3n de Desastres |accessdate=April 14, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090612054045/http://www.gobierno.pr/NR/rdonlyres/49EA64D0-305B-4881-8B85-04B518004BD5/0/Ciclones_en_PR.pdf |archivedate=June 12, 2009 |location=San Juan, Puerto Rico |pages=12\u201313}}</ref>}} was one of the strongest [[tropical cyclone]]s in the [[history of Puerto Rico]]. The center of the storm traversed the island on an east-to-west path in late September&nbsp;1937, killing 225&nbsp;people and inflicting $30&nbsp;million in damage.{{efn|All monetary values are in 1932&nbsp;[[United States dollars]] unless otherwise indicated.|group=nb|name=note-money}} Winds in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], were estimated to have reached at least 120&nbsp;mph (195&nbsp;km/h), causing extensive destruction. The storm's origins can be traced back to at least September&nbsp;25, 1932, when it was a [[tropical storm]] east of the [[Windward Islands]]. Moving west as a compact tropical cyclone, it [[rapid intensification|rapidly intensified]] as it moved across the [[Virgin Islands]] the following day before ultimately making [[landfall (meteorology)|landfall]] on September&nbsp;27 in [[Ceiba, Puerto Rico]], at a peak intensity equivalent to that of a [[List of Category 4 Atlantic hurricanes|Category&nbsp;4 hurricane]] on the modern [[Saffir\u2013Simpson scale]]. The hurricane diminished for the remainder of its duration, egressing Puerto Rico and brushing the southern coast of [[Hispaniola]]. The weakened cyclone passed near [[Jamaica]] on September&nbsp;29 and moved ashore [[British Honduras]] on October&nbsp;1 as a low-end tropical storm, dissipating the next day over southeastern [[Mexico]].\n\nThe San Ciprian Hurricane took an unusual east to west path across [[Puerto Rico]], producing damage across the entire length of the [[United States territory]]. The next storm to follow a similar path was [[Hurricane Georges]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|author=Shawn P. Bennett and Rafael Mojica|year=1998|title=Hurricane Georges Preliminary Storm Report|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=2007-04-12|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/sju/public_report.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014181517/http://www.srh.noaa.gov/sju/public_report.html|archivedate=2008-10-14}}</ref> Overall damage in [[Puerto Rico]] was catastrophic as the storm left $30&nbsp;million (1932&nbsp;USD, equivalent to ${{Inflation|US-GDP|0.03|1932|r=1}}&nbsp;billion in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}}) and 225\u2013257 fatalities. The hurricane also caused moderate damage in the [[Virgin Islands]].<ref name=\"mwr\">{{cite web|author=W.J. Humphreys|year=1932|title=1932 Monthly Weather Review|publisher=NOAA|accessdate=2007-04-12|url=http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/rescue/mwr/060/mwr-060-09-0177.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Meteorological history==\n{{storm path|1932 Atlantic hurricane 9 track.png|alt=A map of the Caribbean Sea showing the path of the hurricane from beginning east of the Leeward Islands and terminating over Central America}}\nThe presence of unusually [[high pressure area|high air pressures]] throughout the Atlantic and eastern North America caused the 1932 San Ciprian hurricane to take an atypical path directed towards the west and west-southwest over its duration.<ref name=\"MWR\">{{cite journal |editor1-last=Humphreys |editor1-first=W. J. |title=West Indian Hurricanes of August and September, 1932 |journal=Monthly Weather Review |date=September 1932 |volume=60 |issue=9 |pages=178\u2013179|doi=10.1175/1520-0493(1932)60<177:TTSOAI>2.0.CO;2 |url=ftp://ftp.library.noaa.gov/docs.lib/htdocs/rescue/mwr/060/mwr-060-09-0177.pdf|via=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |publisher=United States Weather Bureau |location=San Juan, Puerto Rico |format=PDF}}</ref> Details about the hurricane's [[tropical cyclogenesis|genesis]] are unclear due to a lack of contemporaneous weather observations. In 2012, the [[Atlantic hurricane reanalysis|Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory]] (AOML) investigated the storm's history,{{efn|The AOML, through its Hurricane Research Division, [[Atlantic hurricane reanalysis|analyzed]] the system in 2012 as part of a project to reevaluate the [[HURDAT|official hurricane database]] maintained by the [[National Hurricane Center]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Landsea |first1=Christopher W. |last2=Hagen |first2=Andrew |last3=Bredemeyer |first3=William |last4=Carrasco |first4=Cristina |last5=Glenn |first5=David A. |last6=Santiago |first6=Adrian |last7=Strahan-Sakoskie |first7=Donna |last8=Dickinson |first8=Michael |title=A Reanalysis of the 1931\u201343 Atlantic Hurricane Database |journal=Journal of Climate |date=August 2014 |volume=27 |issue=16 |pages=6093\u20136118 |doi=10.1175/JCLI-D-13-00503.1 |url=https://journals.ametsoc.org/doi/pdf/10.1175/JCLI-D-13-00503.1 |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |publisher=American Meteorological Society |location=Boston, Massachusetts |format=PDF}}</ref><ref name=\"Metadata\" /><ref name=\"RAP\">{{cite web |title=Re-Analysis Project |url=https://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/data_sub/re_anal.html |website=Hurricane Research Division |publisher=Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |location=Miami, Florida |date=December 2019}}</ref> Their assessment of the 1932 San Ciprian hurricane made alterations to the storm's track and intensity; for instance, the storm's intensity at its Puerto Rico landfall was originally listed as equivalent to a Category&nbsp;2 hurricane.<ref name=\"Metadata\" />|group=nb}} determining that the hurricane's progenitor had developed into a [[tropical storm]] with [[maximum sustained wind|sustained winds]] of 60&nbsp;mph (95&nbsp;km/h) by 06:00&nbsp;[[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]] on September&nbsp;25, 1932.<ref name=\"Metadata\">{{cite web|last1=Landsea|first1=Chris|last2=Anderson|first2=Craig|last3=Bredemeyer|first3=William|last4=Carrasco|first4=Cristina|last5=Charles|first5=Noel|last6=Chenoweth|first6=Michael|last7=Clark|first7=Gil|last8=Delgado|first8=Sandy|last9=Dunion|first9=Jason|last10=Ellis|first10=Ryan|last11=Fernandez-Partagas|first11=Jose|last12=Feuer|first12=Steve|last13=Gamanche|first13=John|last14=Glenn|first14=David|last15=Hagen|first15=Andrew|last16=Hufstetler|first16=Lyle|last17=Mock|first17=Cary|last18=Neumann|first18=Charlie|last19=Perez Suarez|first19=Ramon|last20=Prieto|first20=Ricardo|last21=Sanchez-Sesma|first21=Jorge|last22=Santiago|first22=Adrian|last23=Sims|first23=Jamese|last24=Thomas|first24=Donna|last25=Lenworth|first25=Woolcock|last26=Zimmer|first26=Mark|authorlink1=Christopher Landsea|title=Documentation of Atlantic Tropical Cyclones Changes in HURDAT|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/metadata_master.html|website=[[Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory]]|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|accessdate=March 23, 2020|date=May 2015|location=[[Miami, Florida]]|type=Metadata|at=1932 Storm #9 - 2012 Revision}}</ref> At that point, the storm was amid a period of intensification and centered approximately 340&nbsp;mi (550&nbsp;km) east of [[Antigua]]. Its winds increased as it moved west, reaching [[hurricane-force]] by 12:00&nbsp;UTC on September&nbsp;25.<ref name=\"IBTrACS\">{{cite web |title=1932 Major Hurricane NOT_NAMED (1932269N17303)|url=http://www.atms.unca.edu/ibtracs/ibtracs_v04r00/index.php?name=v04r00-1932269N17303 |website=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship (IBTrACS) |publisher=[[University of North Carolina at Asheville]] |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |location=[[Asheville, North Carolina]]}}</ref> Early the next day, the hurricane passed near Antigua and [[Saint Barthelemy]], and later between [[Saint Thomas]]{{dn|date=April 2020}} and [[Saint Croix]], tracking west-northwest at roughly 10&nbsp;mph (15&nbsp;km/h).<ref name=\"MWR\" /> Around 13:00&nbsp;UTC on September&nbsp;26, the center of the storm passed near [[Saba]] with winds of 140&nbsp;mph (220&nbsp;km/h);{{efn|[[HURDAT]], the official database for the intensities and tracks of Atlantic tropical cyclones,<ref name=\"RevisedHURDAT\">{{cite web |last1=Landsea |first1=Chris |last2=Franklin |first2=James |last3=Beven |first3=Jack |title=The revised Atlantic hurricane database (HURDAT2) |url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/data/hurdat/hurdat2-format-atlantic.pdf |publisher=National Hurricane Center |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |location=Miami, Florida |format=PDF |date=May 2015}}</ref> lists the maximum sustained winds of storms to the nearest five [[knot (unit)|knots]].<ref name=\"AOMLHURDATGuide\">{{cite web |title=Original HURDAT Format |url=https://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/data_sub/hurdat.html |website=Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory |publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |location=Miami, Florida}}</ref> Conversions to miles per hour (mph) and kilometers per hours (km/h) for values drawn from this database are derived from the original value in knots and rounded to the nearest five.|name=note-hurdat|group=nb}} the steep [[pressure gradient]] measured on that island was indicative of a small and [[rapid intensification|rapidly intensifying hurricane]].<ref name=\"Metadata\" />\n\nAt around 04:00&nbsp;UTC on September&nbsp;27, the compact hurricane made [[landfall (meteorology)|landfall]] on [[Puerto Rico]] near [[Ensenada Honda (Ceiba, Puerto Rico)|Ensenada Honda]] in the municipality of [[Ceiba, Puerto Rico|Ceiba]]. Upon moving ashore, the hurricane had sustained winds estimated at 145&nbsp;mph (230&nbsp;km/h){{efn|name=note-hurdat}} and a minimum central pressure of 943&nbsp;[[bar (unit)|mbar]] ([[pascal (unit)|hPa]]; 27.85&nbsp;[[inches of mercury|inHg]]), equivalent to a [[List of Category 4 Atlantic hurricanes|Category 4 hurricane]] on the modern [[Saffir\u2013Simpson scale]]. The region of hurricane-force winds was likely no larger than 23&nbsp;mi (37&nbsp;km) in diameter upon landfall, with a [[radius of maximum wind]]s likely smaller than 12&nbsp;mi (19&nbsp;km). The storm's center tracked over Puerto Rico for seven hours on an east-to-west course before emerging into the [[Caribbean Sea]] off [[Aguadilla, Puerto Rico|Aguadilla]].<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> Land interaction with Puerto Rico caused the storm's maximum winds to decrease to 105&nbsp;mph (165&nbsp;km/h);{{efn|name=note-hurdat}} the hurricane maintained this strength until it struck the southern ends of the [[Dominican Republic]] and [[Haiti]] on September&nbsp;28.<ref name=\"MWR\" /><ref name=\"Metadata\" /><ref name=\"IBTrACS\" /> This second landfall weakened the system significantly, reducing the winds to 45&nbsp;mph (75&nbsp;km/h).{{efn|name=note-hurdat}}<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> The storm took a slightly south of west heading for the rest of its duration, passing near [[Jamaica]] on September&nbsp;29.<ref name=\"IBTrACS\" /> According to the AOML, the storm might have weakened to a [[tropical depression]] between September&nbsp;29\u201330 while traversing the western Caribbean.<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> The tropical storm reorganized slightly upon making its final landfall south of [[Belize City]] in [[British Honduras]] at around 18:00&nbsp;UTC on October&nbsp;1 with winds of 45&nbsp;mph (75&nbsp;km/h).{{efn|name=note-hurdat}} It progressed west-southwest into southeastern [[Mexico]], weakening before dissipating on October&nbsp;2.<ref name=\"Metadata\" />\n\n{{clear}}\n==Preparations==\nThe [[Weather Bureau|United States Weather Bureau]] office in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]] was first made aware of the storm's presence on September&nbsp;26, following a report of the passage of a \"moderate disturbance\" near Antigua.<ref name=\"MWR\" />  Its first storm bulletin was issued that evening after the center of the storm passed between Saint Thomas and Saint Croix, noting the rapidity of the storm's movement and its small size.<ref name=\"MWR\" /><ref name=\"MayStrikeSection\">{{cite news |title=Hurricane May Strike Section of Puerto Rico |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34065415/|via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=The News-Herald |agency=United Press |issue=16046 |date=September 26, 1932 |location=Franklin, Pennsylvania |page=1}}</ref> This and subsequent bulletins were disseminated in Puerto Rico by the [[Government of Puerto Rico|territorial government]], the [[U.S. Navy]], and local radio station [[WKAQ (AM)|WKAQ]]. The San Juan Weather Bureau office lauded these bodies in their report on the storm published in the ''[[Monthly Weather Review]]'', writing that \"the loss of life and property damaged were materially reduced\" due to their efforts.<ref name=\"MWR\" /> There were 18&nbsp;hours of advance warning for San Juan before the hurricane struck.<ref name=\"WestIndianHurricanes\">{{cite journal |last1=Cook |first1=Melville T. |title=West Indian Hurricanes |journal=The Scientific Monthly |date=1933 |volume=37 |issue=4 |pages=307\u2013315 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/15604 |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |issn=0096-3771}}</ref> The bureau continued to issue advisories concerning the storm twice daily through October&nbsp;1.<ref name=\"MWR\" />\n\nAt the beginning of the [[1932 Atlantic hurricane season]], the [[Governor of Puerto Rico]], [[James R. Beverly]], directed mayors in the territory to organize municipal emergency committees, requiring each to hoist hurricane [[flag signals]] at the cathedrals and city halls of every town whenever a hurricane warning was in effect. Mayors and police forces in Puerto were advised by the Weather Bureau's first statements on the storm to begin safeguarding lives and property. A meeting was held on the afternoon of September&nbsp;26 between the governor, heads of executive departments, the manager of the Puerto Rican chapter of the [[American Red Cross]], and other prominent citizens to formulate plans of actions for possible emergencies arising from the hurricane's passage; these included the mobilization of crews to repair communications infrastructure and police-assisted evacuation of vulnerable people into the sturdiest buildings.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> The American Red Cross in the continental U.S. also prepared to send aid to Puerto Rico when necessary.<ref name=\"RedCrossPreparesSendAid\">{{cite news |title=Red Cross Prepares to Send Aid to Puerto Rico |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48435866/|via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The News-Herald |agency=United Press |issue=16047 |date=September 27, 1932 |location=Franklin, Pennsylvania|page=1}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Dominican Republic]], the hurricane's approach triggered fears of a second disaster as that country was still recovering from the destruction by the [[1930 Dominican Republic Hurricane]] two years earlier.<ref name=\"sdh\">{{cite web|author=Syracuse Herald|year=1932|title=San Domingo and Haiti in the storms path|accessdate=2007-04-18|url=http://www.thehurricanearchive.com/Viewer.aspx?img=51364509&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=0&currentPage=0|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921000811/http://www.thehurricanearchive.com/Viewer.aspx?img=51364509&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=0&currentPage=0|archive-date=2017-09-21|url-status=dead}}</ref> The concern prompted residents to close businesses and evacuate; some sought to nearby churches for shelter.<ref name=\"tvm\">{{cite web|author=United Press|year=1932|title=Long Trail of death and damage left by the storm|publisher=The Vidette-Messenger|accessdate=2007-04-18|url=http://www.thehurricanearchive.com/Viewer.aspx?img=56650985&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=0&currentPage=10}}{{Dead link|date=February 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In [[Jamaica]], meteorologists forecast the storm to move north of the island after passing over [[Port-au-Prince]], [[Haiti]]. The track of the storm prompted the forecasters to issue advisories for oceangoing [[ships]] and small watercraft.<ref name=\"tglen\">{{cite web|author=The Daily Gleaner|year=1932|title=Jamaica in the danger zone|accessdate=2007-04-19|url=http://www.thehurricanearchive.com/Viewer.aspx?img=17604907&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=0&currentPage=0}}{{Dead link|date=February 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The countries of [[Honduras]] and [[Belize]] also took preparations ahead of the storm as people closed shops and other businesses in anticipation of the storm's landfall.<ref>{{cite web|author=Associated Press|year=1932|title=Honduras shops close as hurricane nears|publisher=The Syracuse Herald|accessdate=2007-04-19|url=http://www.thehurricanearchive.com/Viewer.aspx?img=23989821&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=0&currentPage=0}}{{Dead link|date=February 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n[[File:Hurrpaths.JPG|thumb|300px|The tracks of three Puerto Rican hurricanes, including the 1932&nbsp;storm|alt=Map of three hurricane tracks across Puerto Rico and the Greater Antilles]]\n===Virgin Islands===\nThe hurricane's small size was evidenced by wind observations at Saint Thomas and Saint Croix, which are located roughly 45&nbsp;mi (75&nbsp;km) apart. Despite the center of the hurricane passing between the islands, neither island experienced hurricane-force winds, their speeds only reaching 60&nbsp;mph (95&nbsp;km/h).<ref name=\"Metadata\" /><ref name=\"MWR\" /> Moderate damage occurred on Saint Barth\u00e9lemy, [[Saint John, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint John]], Saint Thomas, and [[Tortola]]. Estimated winds of 60\u201390&nbsp;mph (95\u2013145&nbsp;km/h) swept across Saint Barthelemy.<ref name=\"MWR\" /> Radio antennas were blown down by the winds in Saba.<ref name=\"MWR\" /> The firing of warning guns on Saint Thomas 90&nbsp;minutes before the storm's arrival allowed the island's populace to seek shelter. Many houses were damaged and wires and trees were blown down on the island. Small ships capsized in the Saint Thomas harbor. Legislative elections were postponed due to the inclement conditions. Another two passenger-filled [[sloop]]s in Tortola were lost.<ref name=\"VirginIslandsAreStruckByStorm\">{{cite news |title=Virgin Islands Are Struck by Tropical Storm |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48436384/|via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The News-Herald |agency=United Press |issue=16047 |date=September 27, 1932 |location=Franklin, Pennsylvania|page=1}}</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that the hurricane killed 15 people in the [[Virgin Islands]].<ref>{{cite news|author=New York Times|title=SAN JUAN DAMAGED BADLY|accessdate=2007-04-25|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/09/28/archives/san-juan-damaged-badly-120mile-wind-levels-towns-drives-ships.html | work=The New York Times | date=1932-09-28}}</ref>\n\n===Puerto Rico===\nForty-nine [[municipalities of Puerto Rico]] were affected by the storm to varying degrees, with devastation wrought across the northern half of the territory.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> The hurricane's effects killed 257&nbsp;people;<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> most of these fatalities were due to the collapse of buildings, with wind-blown debris and drownings also responsible for some deaths.<ref name=\"MWR\" /> Over 4,820&nbsp;others were injured.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> Though people took shelter in buildings thought to be safe, only well-built masonry and concrete structures withstood the storm in the hardest-hit areas. Concrete buildings made of concrete with a [[properties of concrete|water-to-cement ratio]] and improperly or poorly anchored roofs were destroyed, killing many. Homes with corrugated iron sheet roofs attached using smooth or twisted nails, common in San Juan, were unroofed.<ref name=\"MWR\" /> In total, 45,554&nbsp;houses were razed and another 47,876&nbsp;were partially destroyed.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> The severity of the damage was equivalent to that of an F3&nbsp;tornado on the [[Fujita scale]].<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> Writing to the [[United States Secretary of War]] in 1933, Beverly described the damage was more severe than the [[1928 Okeechobee hurricane|1928 San Felipe hurricane]] for the areas affected.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> Nearly 500,000&nbsp;animals were also killed, including cows, goats, horses, pigs, and poultry.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" />\n\nThe steamships ''Jean'' and ''Acacia'' took refuge at Ensenada Honda, where the hurricane made landfall. Both ships were [[ship grounding|grounded]] by the storm but were refloated after unloading cargo. Several pier buildings at the [[Port of San Juan]]  sustained heavy damage. The three-masted [[schooner]] ''Gaviota'' was wrecked in the harbor. The [[bridge (nautical)|bridge]] and [[ship's boat]]s of another vessel in the harbor were blown away.<ref name=\"MWR\" /> Many smaller ships along the waterfront were driven aground.<ref name=\"PlacedAt200\" /> Telephone and telegraph lines between [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]] and the eastern parts of Puerto Rico were disrupted on the night of September&nbsp;26. The worst of the storm reached San Juan shortly after midnight on the morning of September&nbsp;27 and lasted for about three hours;<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> hurricane-force winds lasted for six hours.<ref name=\"WestIndianHurricanes\" /> Winds of at least 120&nbsp;mph (195&nbsp;km/h) occurred in San Juan, though the local [[measurement tower]] measured a peak wind of 66&nbsp;mph (106&nbsp;km/h) before it was toppled by the storm.<ref name=\"MWR\" /> In San Juan, [[Hato Rey]], and [[R\u00edo Piedras, Puerto Rico|R\u00edo Piedras]], hundreds of homes were blown away and trees were uprooted. The carnage littered streets with debris.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> All communication and electric poles and wires were knocked down.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> WKAQ's [[Radio masts and towers|radio towers]] lay toppled and contorted by the wind.<ref name=\"PlacedAt200\">{{cite news |title=Storm's Dead Placed at 200 in Puerto Rico |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48736951/|via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 14, 2020 |work=The Miami Herald |agency=Associated Press |issue=301|volume=22 |location=Miami, Florida |page=1}}</ref>\n\nReports indicated that all homes collapsed in [[Fajardo, Puerto Rico|Fajardo]] and [[Toa Alta, Puerto Rico|Toa Alta]]. Many small towns outside of the San Juan area were left in similar circumstances.<ref name=\"HurricaneLeavesHeavyDeath\">{{cite news |last1=Beverley |first1=James R. |title=Hurricane Leaves Heavy Death Toll in Antilles Islands |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48736440/|via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 14, 2020 |work=The Napa Journal |agency=United Press |issue=231|volume=79 |date=August 28, 1932 |location=Napa, California|page=1}}</ref>\n\nRainfall totals in Puerto Rico were lower overall than in other hurricanes of similar strength. The maximum total of {{cvt|16.70|in|mm}} was measured in [[Maricao, Puerto Rico|Maricao]].<ref name=\"MWR\" />  Damage to both property and crops amounted to $35.6&nbsp;million, with $15.6&nbsp;million inflicted upon property and and $20&nbsp;million inflicted upon crops. The Puerto Rican Department of Commerce that the damage parlayed into $31.2&nbsp;million in economic losses for agriculture.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> The main [[citrus]]-producing regions of Puerto Rico were located within the swath of the heaviest damage; its losses accounted for the largest proportion of crop losses. Though the main coffee tree plantations did not experience the storm's strongest winds, they were heavily damaged by fallen banana trees; banana trees had been planted to provide temporary shading for the new coffee crop following the 1928 San Felipe hurricane but were susceptible to moderate winds. The toll inflicted on citrus and coffee trees delayed their harvests by several years. The hurricane rendered other crops a total loss, though to an extent recoverable within a [[growing season]].<ref name=\"MWR\" /> Approximately $2.4&nbsp;million worth of agricultural plantations and structures constructed using recovery funds from the 1928&nbsp;hurricane were destroyed.<ref name=\"PRC\" /> Forests along the [[Sierra de Luquillo]] were defoliated and exhibited high tree mortality after being lashed by the heavy rains and strong winds.<ref name=\"ARainforestChronicle\">{{cite journal |last1=Crow |first1=Thomas R. |title=A Rainforest Chronicle: A 30-Year Record of Change in Structure and Composition at El Verde, Puerto Rico |journal=Biotropica |date=March 1980 |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=42 |doi=10.2307/2387772}}</ref> East of the Puerto Rican mainland, [[Culebra, Puerto Rico|Culebra]] and [[Vieques]] also sustained heavy damage.<ref name=\"MWR\" /> \n\n===Dominican Republic===\nIn the [[Dominican Republic]], the hurricane produced 90&nbsp;mph (145&nbsp;km/h) winds in [[San Pedro de Macor\u00eds]] and 50&nbsp;mph (80&nbsp;km/h) winds in [[Santo Domingo]].<ref name=\"MWR\" /> Many houses in the interior villages were unroofed.<ref name=\"PuertoRicoWorstSufferer\">{{cite news |title=Puerto Rico Worst Sufferer in Tropic Storm |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48736713/|via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 14, 2020 |work=The Napa Journal |agency=United Press |issue=231|volume=79 |date=August 28, 1932 |location=Napa, California|page=1}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nIn the [[Virgin Islands]], officials and the [[Red Cross]] provided $25,000&nbsp;dollars (1932&nbsp;USD) in relief aid.<ref>{{cite web|author=Associated Press|year=1932|title=Newspaper Report on the Hurricane|publisher=Galveston Daily News|accessdate=2007-04-25|url=http://www.thehurricanearchive.com/Viewer.aspx?img=45206887&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=0&currentPage=0}}{{Dead link|date=February 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nWorkers from the Puerto Rican Department of the Interior, assisted by prisoners and volunteers, quickly cleared roads of debris once the storm passed. [[United States National Guard|National Guard]] and Red Cross personnel were promptly dispatched into the affected areas to aid recovery efforts; medical and food supplies were distributed in the larger impacted municipalities within 24&nbsp;hours of the storm's passage.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> Some of the relief efforts were also managed by the Puerto Rican Hurricane Relief Commission that was formed in response to the 1928&nbsp;hurricane.<ref name=\"PRC\">{{cite report|title=Fourth Annual Report of the Puerto Rican Hurricane Relief Commission |date=December 2, 1932 |publisher=Puerto Rican Hurricane Relief Commission |pages=1\u20136}}</ref> For the 1932&nbsp;storm, a Hurricane Relief and Rehabilitation Commission was formed on September&nbsp;27 in cooperation with the Red Cross, split into an executive committee and two subcommittees. One subcommittee was tasked with enforcing [[price control]]s while the other was tasked with raising relief funds for immediate purchases of materials and to supplement the Red Cross's efforts; nearly $75,000 was collected by this second committee. The funds augmented an emergency fund established by the Puerto Rican government in April&nbsp;1932; $165,000 in relief was sourced from this fund, including a $50,000 loan to the Fruit Growers Cooperative Credit Association for the recovery of the citrus crop and acqusition of fertilizer. Food and shelter relief was administered by the Red Cross. Additional supplies were made available to these committees by the American military stationed in Puerto Rico. Two reconnaissance flights were arranged on September&nbsp;27 and September&nbsp;28 to better determine the extent and severity of the damage across northern Puerto Rico. Teachers were enlisted by the Department of Education to appraise the total property damage while while crop damage was tallied by the Commissioner of Agriculture and Commerce. The Red Cross reported that 76,925&nbsp;families were in \"actual distress\" due to the hurricane.<ref name=\"PRReport33\" /> The destruction of homes rendered 25,000&nbsp;families homeless.<ref name=\"Rodriguez\">{{cite journal |last1=Rodr\u00edguez |first1=Havid\u00e1n |title=A Socioeconomic Analysis of Hurricanes in Puerto Rico: An Overview of Disaster Mitigation and Preparedness |journal=Hurricanes: Climate and Socioeconomic Impacts |date=1997 |pages=121\u2013143 |doi=10.1007/978-3-642-60672-4_7 |publisher=Springer}}</ref> Total economic losses from the storm were equivalent to 20&nbsp;percent of Puerto Rico's [[gross national income|gross income]].<ref name=\"Sotomayor\">{{cite journal |last1=Sotomayor |first1=Orlando |title=Fetal and infant origins of diabetes and ill health: Evidence from Puerto Rico's 1928 and 1932 hurricanes |journal=Economics & Human Biology |date=July 2013 |volume=11 |issue=3 |pages=281\u2013293 |doi=10.1016/j.ehb.2012.02.009 |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones|Puerto Rico}}\n*[[1867 San Narciso hurricane]]&nbsp;\u2013 \n*[[1876 San Felipe hurricane]]&nbsp;\u2013 \n*[[Hurricane Georges]]&nbsp;\u2013 the first hurricane after 1932 to take an east-to-west path across Puerto Rico<ref name=\"SJUGeorges\">{{cite web |last1=Bennett |first1=Shawn P. |last2=Mojica |first2=Rafael |title=Hurricane Georges Preliminary Storm Report |url=https://www.weather.gov/sju/1998_georges |website=National Weather Service San Juan, Puerto Rico |publisher=National Weather Service |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |location=San Juan, Puerto Rico}}</ref>\n*[[Hurricane Maria]]&nbsp;\u2013 the first storm after 1932 to strike Puerto Rico with at least Category&nbsp;4 hurricane winds<ref name=\"MariaReliefEffort\">{{cite news |last1=Meyer |first1=Robinson |title=What's Happening With the Relief Effort in Puerto Rico? |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2017/10/what-happened-in-puerto-rico-a-timeline-of-hurricane-maria/541956/ |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |work=The Atlantic |date=October 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{1932 Atlantic hurricane season buttons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1932 San Ciprian}}\n[[Category:1932 Atlantic hurricane season|San Ciprian]]\n[[Category:Category 4 Atlantic hurricanes]]\n[[Category:1932 natural disasters|San Ciprian Hurricane]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in Puerto Rico]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1932_San_Ciprian_hurricane"}
{"title_page": "Elements of art", "text_new": "[[File:Elements of art.jpg|thumb|The seven elements of art, with the addition of point (perspective).]]\n'''Elements of art''' are stylistic features that are included within an art piece to help the artist communicate<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://login.uproxy.library.dc-uoit.ca/login?qurl=https://search.proquest.com%2fdocview%2f2130125923%3fpq-origsite%3dprimo|title=Elements of Art: Interpreting Meaning Through the Language of Visual Cues|last=Roxo|first=Justin|date=|website=login.uproxy.library.dc-uoit.ca|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>. The seven most common elements include line, shape, texture, form, space, colour and value, with the additions of mark making, and materiality.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www2.oberlin.edu/amam/asia/sculpture/documents/vocabulary.pdf|title=Vocabulary: Elements of Art, Principles of Art|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> When analyzing these intentionally utilized elements, the viewer is guided towards a deeper understanding of the work.\n\n== Line ==\n[[Line (geometry)|Lines]] are marks moving in a space between two points whereby viewer can visualize the stroke movement, direction and intention based on how the line is oriented.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Lines describe an outline, capable of producing texture according to their [[length]] and [[curve]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.incredibleart.org/files/elements2.htm|title=Visual Arts: Elements and Principles of Design|website=www.incredibleart.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> There are different types of lines artists may use, including, actual, implied, vertical, horizontal, diagonal and [[Contour line|contour]] lines, which all have different functions.<ref name=\":2\" /> Lines are also situational elements, requiring the viewer to have knowledge of the physical world in order to understand their flexibility, rigidity, synthetic nature, or life.<ref name=\":0\" />\n== Shape ==\nA [[shape]] is a [[Two-dimensional space|two-dimensional]] design encased by lines to signify its height and width structure, and can have different values of colour used within it to make it appear [[Three-dimensional space|three-dimensional]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/definition-of-shape-in-art-182463|title=How Would You Define \"Shape\"?|last=Esaak|first=Shelley|website=ThoughtCo|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> In animation, shapes are used to give a character a distinct personality and features, with the animator manipulating the shapes to provide new life.<ref name=\":0\" /> There are different types of shapes an artist can use and fall under either geometrical, defined by mathematics, or organic shapes, created by the artist.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Simplistic, geometrical shapes include circles, triangles and squares, and provide a symbolic and synthetic feeling, whereas acute angled shapes with sharp points are perceived as dangerous shapes.<ref name=\":0\" /> Rectilinear shapes are viewed as dependable and more structurally sound, while curvilinear shapes are chaotic and adaptable.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Form ==\nForm is a three-dimensional object with [[volume]] of height, width and depth.<ref name=\":1\" /> These objects include cubes, spheres and cylinders.<ref name=\":1\" /> Form is often used when referring to physical works of art, like sculptures, as form is connected most closely with three-dimensional works and can be viewed from many angles.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/definition-of-form-in-art-182437|title=The Definition of Form in Art|last=Marder|first=Lisa Marder our editorial process Lisa|website=ThoughtCo|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> In drawn or animated works, form is alluded to by adding [[shading]] and highlights to two-dimensional shapes, giving the illusion of depth.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Color ==\n[[Color|Color]] is an element consisting of hues, of which there are three properties: hue, chroma or intensity, and value.<ref name=\":2\" /> Color is present when light strikes an object and it is reflected back into the eye, a reaction to a hue arising in the optic nerve.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/definition-of-color-in-art-182429|title=How Is Color Defined in Art?|last=Esaak|first=Shelley|website=ThoughtCo|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The first of the properties is [[hue]], which is the distinguishable color, like red, blue or yellow.<ref name=\":5\" /> The next property is value, meaning the lightness or darkness of the hue.<ref name=\":5\" /> The last is chroma or intensity, distinguishing between strong and weak colors.<ref name=\":5\" /> A visual representation of chromatic scale is observable through the color wheel that uses the [[Primary color|primary colors]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Space ==\n[[Space]] refers to the [[Perspective (graphical)|perspective]] (distance between and around) and proportion (size) between shapes and objects and how their relationship with the foreground or background is perceived.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/definition-of-color-in-art-182429|title=How Is Color Defined in Art?|last=Esaak|first=Shelley|website=ThoughtCo|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> There are different types of spaces an artist can achieve for different effect. Positive space refers to the areas of the work with a subject, while negative space is the space without a subject.<ref name=\":6\" /> Open and closed space coincides with three-dimensional art, like sculptures, where open spaces are empty, and closed spaces contain physical sculptural elements.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==Texture==\nTexture is used to describe the surface quality of the work, referencing the types of lines the artist created.<ref name=\":0\" /> The surface quality can either be tactile (real) or strictly visual (implied).<ref name=\":2\" /> Tactile surface quality is mainly seen through three-dimensional works, like sculptures, as the viewer can see and/or feel the different textures present, while visual surface quality describes how the eye perceives the texture based on visual cues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/definition-of-texture-in-art-182468|title=Here's how artists use texture and why it's so important in art|last=Esaak|first=Shelley|website=ThoughtCo|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> \n\n== Value ==\n[[File:ART VALUE SCALE.png|thumb|529x529px|The scale between dark (black) and light (white) values.]]\nValue refers to the degree of perceivable lightness of tones within an image.<ref name=\":1\" /> The element of value is compatible with the term [[luminosity]], and can be \"measured in various units designating [[electromagnetic radiation]]\".<ref name=\":6\" /> The difference in values is often called [[Contrast (vision)|contrast]], and references the lightest (white) and darkest (black) tones of a work of art, with an infinite number of grey variants in between.<ref name=\":6\" /> While it is most relative to the greyscale, though, it is also exemplified within coloured images.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Mark Making and Materiality ==\nMark making is the interaction between the artist and the materials they are using.<ref name=\":0\" /> It provides the viewer of the work with an image of what the artist had done to create the mark, reliving what the artist had done at the time.<ref name=\":0\" /> Materiality is the choice of materials used and how it impacts the work of art and how the viewer perceives it.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Style (visual arts)]]\n*[[Principles of art]]\n*[[Perspective (graphical)]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n== External links ==\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elements Of Art}}\n[[Category:Visual arts theory]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Elements of art.jpg|thumb|The seven elements of art, with the addition of point (perspective).]]\n'''Elements of art''' are stylistic features that are included within an art piece to help the artist communicate<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://login.uproxy.library.dc-uoit.ca/login?qurl=https://search.proquest.com%2fdocview%2f2130125923%3fpq-origsite%3dprimo|title=Elements of Art: Interpreting Meaning Through the Language of Visual Cues|last=Roxo|first=Justin|date=|website=login.uproxy.library.dc-uoit.ca|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>. The seven most common elements include line, shape, texture, form, space, colour and value, with the additions of mark making, and materiality.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www2.oberlin.edu/amam/asia/sculpture/documents/vocabulary.pdf|title=Vocabulary: Elements of Art, Principles of Art|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> When analyzing these intentionally utilized elements, the viewer is guided towards a deeper understanding of the work.\n\n== Line ==\n[[Line (geometry)|Lines]] are marks moving in a space between two points whereby viewer can visualize the stroke movement, direction and intention based on how the line is oriented.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Lines describe an outline, capable of producing texture according to their [[length]] and [[curve]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.incredibleart.org/files/elements2.htm|title=Visual Arts: Elements and Principles of Design|website=www.incredibleart.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> There are different types of lines artists may use, including, actual, implied, vertical, horizontal, diagonal and [[Contour line|contour]] lines, which all have different functions.<ref name=\":2\" /> Lines are also situational elements, requiring the viewer to have knowledge of the physical world in order to understand their flexibility, rigidity, synthetic nature, or life.<ref name=\":0\" />\n== Shape ==\nA [[shape]] is a [[Two-dimensional space|two-dimensional]] design encased by lines to signify its height and width structure, and can have different values of colour used within it to make it appear [[Three-dimensional space|three-dimensional]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/definition-of-shape-in-art-182463|title=How Would You Define \"Shape\"?|last=Esaak|first=Shelley|website=ThoughtCo|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> In animation, shapes are used to give a character a distinct personality and features, with the animator manipulating the shapes to provide new life.<ref name=\":0\" /> There are different types of shapes an artist can use and fall under either geometrical, defined by mathematics, or organic shapes, created by the artist.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Simplistic, geometrical shapes include circles, triangles and squares, and provide a symbolic and synthetic feeling, whereas acute angled shapes with sharp points are perceived as dangerous shapes.<ref name=\":0\" /> Rectilinear shapes are viewed as dependable and more structurally sound, while curvilinear shapes are chaotic and adaptable.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Form ==\nForm is a three-dimensional object with [[volume]] of height, width and depth.<ref name=\":1\" /> These objects include cubes, spheres and cylinders.<ref name=\":1\" /> Form is often used when referring to physical works of art, like sculptures, as form is connected most closely with three-dimensional works and can be viewed from many angles.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/definition-of-form-in-art-182437|title=The Definition of Form in Art|last=Marder|first=Lisa Marder our editorial process Lisa|website=ThoughtCo|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> In drawn or animated works, form is alluded to by adding [[shading]] and highlights to two-dimensional shapes, giving the illusion of depth.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Colour ==\n[[Color|Colour]] is an element consisting of hues, of which there are three properties: hue, chroma or intensity, and value.<ref name=\":2\" /> Colour is present when light strikes an object and it is reflected back into the eye, a reaction to a hue arising in the optic nerve.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/definition-of-color-in-art-182429|title=How Is Color Defined in Art?|last=Esaak|first=Shelley|website=ThoughtCo|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The first of the properties is [[hue]], which is the distinguishable colour, like red, blue or yellow.<ref name=\":5\" /> The next property is value, meaning the lightness or darkness of the hue.<ref name=\":5\" /> The last is chroma or intensity, distinguishing between strong and weak colours.<ref name=\":5\" /> A visual representation of chromatic scale is observable through the colour wheel that uses the [[Primary color|primary colours]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Space ==\n[[Space]] refers to the [[Perspective (graphical)|perspective]] (distance between and around) and proportion (size) between shapes and objects and how their relationship with the foreground or background is perceived.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/definition-of-color-in-art-182429|title=How Is Color Defined in Art?|last=Esaak|first=Shelley|website=ThoughtCo|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> There are different types of spaces an artist can achieve for different effect. Positive space refers to the areas of the work with a subject, while negative space is the space without a subject.<ref name=\":6\" /> Open and closed space coincides with three-dimensional art, like sculptures, where open spaces are empty, and closed spaces contain physical sculptural elements.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==Texture==\nTexture is used to describe the surface quality of the work, referencing the types of lines the artist created.<ref name=\":0\" /> The surface quality can either be tactile (real) or strictly visual (implied).<ref name=\":2\" /> Tactile surface quality is mainly seen through three-dimensional works, like sculptures, as the viewer can see and/or feel the different textures present, while visual surface quality describes how the eye perceives the texture based on visual cues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/definition-of-texture-in-art-182468|title=Here's how artists use texture and why it's so important in art|last=Esaak|first=Shelley|website=ThoughtCo|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> \n\n== Value ==\n[[File:ART VALUE SCALE.png|thumb|529x529px|The scale between dark (black) and light (white) values.]]\nValue refers to the degree of perceivable lightness of tones within an image.<ref name=\":1\" /> The element of value is compatible with the term [[luminosity]], and can be \"measured in various units designating [[electromagnetic radiation]]\".<ref name=\":6\" /> The difference in values is often called [[Contrast (vision)|contrast]], and references the lightest (white) and darkest (black) tones of a work of art, with an infinite number of grey variants in between.<ref name=\":6\" /> While it is most relative to the greyscale, though, it is also exemplified within coloured images.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Mark Making and Materiality ==\nMark making is the interaction between the artist and the materials they are using.<ref name=\":0\" /> It provides the viewer of the work with an image of what the artist had done to create the mark, reliving what the artist had done at the time.<ref name=\":0\" /> Materiality is the choice of materials used and how it impacts the work of art and how the viewer perceives it.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Style (visual arts)]]\n*[[Principles of art]]\n*[[Perspective (graphical)]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n== External links ==\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elements Of Art}}\n[[Category:Visual arts theory]]\n", "name_user": "Dmv.Allison", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eColor", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elements_of_art"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sweden", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Sweden}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]] in [[Sweden]]\n| map1            = COVID-19_Outbreak_Cases_in_Sweden_by_Number_with_Legend.svg\n| legend1         = {{Center|Map of confirmed cases in Sweden\n(absolute numbers)<ref name=\"FHM_Official_stats\"/>\n}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Sweden]]\n| first_case      = [[J\u00f6nk\u00f6ping]]\n| arrival_date    = 24 January 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=24|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| deaths          = 1,203<ref name=\"FHM_Official_stats\"/> as of 15 April \n| confirmed_cases = 11,927<ref name=\"FHM_Official_stats\"/> as of 15 April\n| severe_cases    = 954<ref name=\"FHM_Official_stats\"/> in [[intensive care unit|ICU]] as of 15 April\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/smittskydd-beredskap/utbrott/aktuella-utbrott/covid-19/ Swedish Public Health Agency Covid-19] (''in Swedish'')\n}}\n<!-- General overview -->\n\nThe [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing pandemic]] of [[COVID-19|coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2), was confirmed to have reached [[Sweden]] on 31 January 2020, when a woman returning from [[Wuhan]] tested positive. On 26 February, following outbreaks [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|in Italy]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|in Iran]], multiple travel-related clusters appeared in Sweden. [[Transmission (medicine)#Definition and related terms|Community transmission]] was confirmed on 9 March in the [[Stockholm Regional Council|Stockholm region]]. Since then, individuals in every [[Counties of Sweden|l\u00e4n (county)]] have tested positive for COVID-19. The first death was reported on 11 March in [[Stockholm]], a case of community transmission.\n<!-- References in main text, not lead--><!-- Restrictions -->\n\nSweden has, unlike many other countries, not applied any [[lockdown]], with most measures being voluntary. The [[Swedish Constitution|Swedish constitution]] prohibits [[Ministerstyre|ministerial rule]] and mandates that the relevant government body, here an expert agency \u2014 the [[Public Health Agency of Sweden|Public Health Agency]] \u2014 must initiate all actions to prevent the virus. The government can follow agency recommendations, as it has with legislation limiting [[freedom of assembly]], temporarily banning gatherings of over 50 individuals, banning people from visiting nursing homes, as well as physically closing [[secondary school]]s and [[University|universities]].<!--Reference in text--> Primary schools have remained open, in part to avoid healthcare workers staying home with their children.<!-- References in main text, not lead--><!-- Recommendations and health care changes -->\n\nThe Public Health Agency and government issued recommendations to: if possible, work from home; avoid unnecessary travel within the country; to engage in [[social distancing]]; and for people above 70 to stay at home, as much as possible. Those with even minimal symptoms which could be COVID-19, are recommended to stay home. The '[[Sick leave#Sweden|''karensdag'']]' or initial day without paid [[Sick leave|sick-leave]] has been removed by the government and the length of time one can stay home with pay without a doctor's note has been raised from 7 to 21 days.<!-- References in main text, not lead--><!-- Case number-->\n\n{{As of|2020|4|15|df=EU}}, there were 11,927 confirmed cases, of which 954 received intensive care, and 1,203 deaths related to the newly found virus in Sweden, with [[Stockholm County]] being the most affected.<ref name=\"FHM_Official_stats\">{{Cite web|url=https://experience.arcgis.com/experience/09f821667ce64bf7be6f9f87457ed9aa|title=Antal fall av covid-19 i Sverige - data uppdateras dagligen kl 11.30|last=|first=|date=2020-03-30|website=Public Health Agency of Sweden \u2014 Official statistics at arcgis|publisher=[[Public Health Agency of Sweden]] (Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09|layurl=https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/smittskydd-beredskap/utbrott/aktuella-utbrott/covid-19/aktuellt-epidemiologiskt-lage/|laysource=Antal fall av covid-19 \u2014 Statistik \u2013 antal fall covid-19|language=Swedish|quote=\"Data updated daily at 11:30 [CET]\"}}</ref><!-- Reference added for statement that is subject to frequent change-->\n\n==Background==\n{{Further|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#History}}\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] (nCoV) was the cause of a [[COVID-19|respiratory illness]] in a cluster of people in [[Wuhan]], in [[Hubei|Hubei province]], [[China]], who had initially come to the WHO's attention on 31 December 2019. This cluster was initially linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in Wuhan City.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A few days later, on 16 January, the [[Swedish Public Health Agency]] issued a press release highlighting the discovery of the novel coronavirus, and the agency monitoring the situation. The risk of spread to Sweden was described as \"very low\" as there was yet no evidence that the virus [[transmission (medicine)|could spread between humans]], but they recommended that individuals developing [[cough]] or [[fever]] after visiting Wuhan should seek medical care, and asked for healthcare professionals to be observant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/januari/nytt-coronavirus-upptackt-i-kina/|title=Nytt coronavirus uppt\u00e4ckt i Kina \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se|language=sv|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the World Health Organization classified the novel Coronavirus as a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]] on 30 January and demanded that all member states should cooperate to prevent further spread of the virus, the Agency requested for the Swedish government to classify the novel disease as a [[notifiable disease|notifiable infectious disease]] in the [[Notifiable diseases in Sweden|Swedish Communicable Diseases Act]] as both [[Notifiable diseases in Sweden#List of notifiable diseases|dangerous to public health]] (allm\u00e4nfarlig) and [[Notifiable diseases in Sweden#List of notifiable diseases|dangerous to society]] (samh\u00e4llsfarlig), where [[contact tracing]] is required,<ref name=fhmpress200131>{{cite web |title=Utbrottet av nytt coronavirus kr\u00e4ver samordnade insatser internationellt \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten |url=https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/januari/utbrottet-av-nytt-coronavirus-kraver-samordnade-insatser-internationellt/ |website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se |accessdate=5 April 2020 |language=sv |date=30 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten f\u00f6resl\u00e5r att nytt coronavirus tas upp i smittskyddslagen \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten |url=https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/januari/folkhalsomyndigheten-foreslar-att-nytt-coronavirus-tas-upp-i-smittskyddslagen/ |website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Blohm |first1=Lisa |title=Coronavirus p\u00e5 v\u00e4g klassas som samh\u00e4llsfarligt |url=https://www.dagensmedicin.se/artiklar/2020/01/31/coronavirus-pa-vag-klassas-som-samhallsfarligt/ |website=Dagens Medicin |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=sv}}</ref> giving the disease the same legislative status as [[Ebola]], [[SARS]] and [[Smallpox]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Anm\u00e4lningspliktiga sjukdomar \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten |url=https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/smittskydd-beredskap/overvakning-och-rapportering/anmalningspliktiga-sjukdomar/ |website=www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=sv |date=3 March 2020}}</ref> The agency also announced that they have [[ COVID-19 testing|analysing methods]] that can diagnose a case of the novel disease \u2018within hours\u2019 after testing, and that such tests had already been carried out, but that all had turned out negative.<ref name=fhmpress200131 />\n\n===Preparedness===\nIn the [[Global Health Security Index|2019 Global Health Security Index]] published by the [[Johns Hopkins Center for Health Security]], Sweden was considered to be one of the \u2018most prepared\u2019 countries in the world for an epidemic or a pandemic, ranking 7th overall. Sweden was considered to be among the countries most capable of preventing the emergence of a new pathogen, early detection of an epidemic and reporting an epidemic of international concern and having a low risk environment. However, the [[Healthcare in Sweden|Swedish health system]] received a lower score, questioning if it was sufficient and robust enough to treat the sick and protect health workers.<ref>{{cite web |title=GHS Index: Findings and Recommendations |url=https://www.ghsindex.org/ |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nBefore the outbreak of the new coronavirus, Sweden had a relatively low [[List of countries by hospital beds|number of hospital beds per capita]], with 2.2 beds per 1000 people (2017),<ref>{{cite web|title=Health Care Resources|url=http://stats.oecd.org/index.aspx?DataSetCode=HEALTH_REAC#|website=stats.oecd.org|accessdate=17 October 2017}}</ref> and an [[List of countries by hospital beds#Numbers|intensive care unit (ICU) beds per capita]] of 5.8 per 100.000 people.<ref name=\"Rhodes2012\">{{Cite journal |last=Rhodes |first=A. |last2=Ferdinande |first2=P. |last3=Flaatten |first3=H. |last4=Guidet |first4=B. |last5=Metnitz |first5=P. G. |last6=Moreno |first6=R. P. |date=2012-10-01 |title=The variability of critical care bed numbers in Europe |journal=Intensive Care Medicine |language=en |volume=38 |issue=10 |pages=1647\u20131653 |doi=10.1007/s00134-012-2627-8 |pmid=22777516 |issn=1432-1238}}</ref> Both numbers were lower than most countries in the [[European Union|EU]]. The total number of ICU beds in Swedish hospitals were 526.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Frejdeman |first1=Hannah |title=\u201dEfterrapportering att v\u00e4nta efter helgen\u201d |url=https://www.svd.se/just-nu-folkhalsomyndigheten-haller-presstraff |website=Svenska Dagbladet |language=sv |date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Sweden medical cases chart}}\n<!-- NOTICE\n     Keep this section short!\n     Sections below are\n     more detailed.\n     Minor details can\n     be added to the\n     timeline below! -->\nOn 31 January, the first Swedish case was confirmed in a woman in [[J\u00f6nk\u00f6ping]] who had travelled to Sweden from Wuhan on 24 January directly from Wuhan. The case was fully isolated and there are no reports of further spread.<ref name=\"fhm0226\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gp.se/1.24829340|title=F\u00f6rsta svenska coronafallet kliniskt frisk|last=Abrahamsson|first=Anders|date=3 March 2020|website=gp.se|language=sv|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> The second case was diagnosed at [[Sahlgrenska University Hospital]], [[Gothenburg]] on 26 February, after a man who had recently returned from northern [[Italy]] following the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|COVID-19 outbreak in Italy]] had developed symptoms.<ref name=\"bolin1\">{{Cite news|last=Bolin|first=Mattias|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/vast/bekraftat-coronafall-i-goteborg-person-vardas-pa-sahlgrenska|title=Bekr\u00e4ftat coronafall i G\u00f6teborg \u2013 person v\u00e5rdas p\u00e5 Sahlgrenska|date=26 February 2020|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=26 February 2020|language=sv}}</ref><ref name=\"fhm0226\">{{cite web|url=https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/februari/nytt-bekraftat-fall-av-covid-19/|title=Nytt bekr\u00e4ftat fall av covid-19|date=26 February 2020|website=Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|language=sv|trans-title=New confirmed case of covid-19|url-status=live|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> With five additional cases confirmed on 27 February,<ref>https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/februari/inbjudan-till-presstraff-ytterligare-fall-av-covid-19-i-flera-regioner2/</ref> the Swedish Public Health Agency ('''Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten''<nowiki/>') put out a statement that these cases were all related to travel to high-risk zones and that there was no evidence of [[Transmission (medicine)|community transmission]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/februari/inbjudan-till-presstraff-ytterligare-fall-av-covid-19-i-flera-regioner2/|title=Inbjudan till presstr\u00e4ff: Ytterligare fall av covid-19 i flera regioner \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se|language=sv|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> Disease control measures, including extensive [[contact tracing]] turned up over 200 travel-related cases in the following weeks, all with connection to confirmed cases or travel to high risk regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/snabbkollen/30-40-i-karantan-pa-stockholmssjukhus|title=M\u00f6jliga fall av inhemsk smitta|date=9 March 2020|website=svt.se|url-status=live|access-date=27 March 2020|language=sv|trans-title=Possible cases of domestic infection}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February, [[Uppsala County]] confirmed its first case in a woman with a travel history to Germany, where she had met with an Italian colleague, and had been admitted to [[Uppsala University Hospital]]<ref name=\"Via TT\">{{cite web|url=https://via.tt.se/embedded/release/patient-med-bekraftat-coronavirus-vardas-pa-akademiska?publisherId=3235664&releaseId=3271133|title=Via TT|website=via.tt.se|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref> after seeking medical attention with flu-like symptoms. [[Halland County|Halland]], [[Norrbotten County|Norrbotten]], [[S\u00f6dermanland County|S\u00f6dermanland]],[[V\u00e4sterbotten County|V\u00e4sterbotten]] and [[\u00d6sterg\u00f6tland County|\u00d6sterg\u00f6tland]] all confirmed their first cases on 9 March.,<ref name=\"news - Region Halland\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.regionhalland.se/nyheter/ett-bekraftat-fall-i-halland-av-coronavirus/|title=news - Region Halland|website=www.regionhalland.se|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Bekr\u00e4ftat fall av coronavirus i S\u00f6r\">{{cite web|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/sormland/bekraftat-fall-av-coronavirus-i-sormland|title=Bekr\u00e4ftat fall av coronavirus i S\u00f6rmland|last=|first=|date=|website=SVT|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"SVT9\">{{cite news|last1=Larsson|first1=Erica|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/norrbotten/forsta-coronafallet-i-norrbotten|title=F\u00f6rsta coronafallet konstaterat i Norrbotten|date=9 March 2020|access-date=11 March 2020|publisher=Sveriges Television|last2=Haupt|first2=Inger|language=Swedish}}</ref><ref name=\"vasterbotten0309\">{{cite web|url=https://www.regionvasterbotten.se/bekraftade-fall-av-coronavirus-i-vasterbotten|title=Bekr\u00e4ftade fall av coronavirus i V\u00e4sterbotten|website=Region V\u00e4sterbotten|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"regionostergotland.se\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.regionostergotland.se/Om-regionen/Pressrum/Nyheter/ett-fall-av-coronavirus-bekraftat-i-ostergotland/|title=Ett fall av coronavirus bekr\u00e4ftat i \u00d6sterg\u00f6taland|website=www.regionostergotland.se|language=sv|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"SVT9\"/> This came as the first cases of community transmission was confirmed among two patients who had sought care at [[Saint G\u00f6ran Hospital|S:t G\u00f6ran Hospital]], [[Stockholm]], on 6 March.<ref name=\"20employees\">{{Cite news|last=Erlandsson|first=\u00c5sa|url=https://www.svd.se/coronasmittad-pa-st-goran--personal-satt-i-karantan|title=20 anst\u00e4llda i karant\u00e4n \u2013 S:t G\u00f6rans i stabsl\u00e4ge|date=9 March 2020|work=Svenska Dagbladet|access-date=9 March 2020|language=sv|trans-title=20 employees in quarantine - S: t G\u00f6rans in staff position|issn=1101-2412}}</ref> They were assumed to have been infected through community transmission approximately 7 days before seeking care.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}} The following day, [[J\u00e4mtland County|J\u00e4mtland]] and [[V\u00e4sternorrland County|V\u00e4sternorrland]] also confirmed initial cases.<ref name=\"regionjh.se\">{{cite web|url=https://www.regionjh.se/nyheter/pressmeddelanden/rjhpress/enpersonijamtlandslankonstateratsmittadavcoronaviruset.5.55412b91170402c7d222e632.html|title=En person i J\u00e4mtlands l\u00e4n konstaterat smittad av coronaviruset - Region J\u00e4mtland H\u00e4rjedalen|website=regionjh.se|language=sv|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"rvn.se\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rvn.se/sv/Om-regionen/Aktuellt-i-Region-Vasternorrland/Nyheter/tre-personer-i-vasternorrland-smittade-av-coronaviruset/|title=Tre personer i V\u00e4sternorrland smittade av coronaviruset|website=rvn.se|language=sv|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nResponding to indications of local transmission in the [[Stockholm county|Stockholm]] area and [[V\u00e4stra G\u00f6taland County|V\u00e4stra G\u00f6taland]], the Public Health Agency on 10 March raised the risk assessment of community spread from ''moderate'' to ''very high'', which is the highest level.<ref name=\"folkhalsomyndigheten.se\">{{cite web|url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/mars/flera-tecken-pa-samhallsspridning-av-covid-19-i-sverige/|title=Flera tecken p\u00e5 samh\u00e4llsspridning av covid-19 i Sverige \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se|language=sv|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"folkhalsomyndigheten.se\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Stefansson|first=Klara|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/risken-for-coronaspridning-i-sverige-hojs-till-mycket-hog|title=Risken f\u00f6r coronaspridning i Sverige h\u00f6js till \"mycket h\u00f6g\"|date=10 March 2020|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=10 March 2020|language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/mars/flera-tecken-pa-samhallsspridning-av-covid-19-i-sverige/|title=Flera tecken p\u00e5 samh\u00e4llsspridning av Covid-19 i Sverige|last=|first=|date=|website=Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=10 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref> The first death was reported on 11 March, when a person in their 70s from the Stockholm region died in the intensive care unit of [[Karolinska University Hospital]]. The person was reported to have acquired the virus through community transmission, believed to have occurred about one week before death. The person also belonged to a risk group.<ref name=\":33\">{{Cite news|last=Claesson|first=Frida|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/stockholm/en-person-har-avlidit-av-coronaviruset|title=En person har avlidit till f\u00f6ljd av coronaviruset|date=11 March 2020|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=11 March 2020|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nThe COVID-19 outbreak, which the World Health Organization (WHO) declared a pandemic on 11 March,<ref name=\"nyt sports\">{{Cite news|last=Deb|first=Sopan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/11/sports/basketball/warriors-coronavirus-fans.html|title=Sports Leagues Bar Fans and Cancel Games Amid Coronavirus Outbreak|date=11 March 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=12 March 2020|last2=Cacciola|first2=Scott|issn=0362-4331|last3=Stein|first3=Marc}}</ref> has had a disparate impact on different areas of Sweden.\n\nThe Public Health Agency of Sweden declared on 13 March that stopping the spread of Covid-19 has entered a \"new phase\" which requires \"other efforts\". The continued focus is now to delay spread among the population and to protect the elderly and most vulnerable against the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/mars/ny-fas-kraver-nya-insatser-mot-covid-19/|title=Ny fas kr\u00e4ver nya insatser mot covid-19 \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se|language=sv|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe health agency believed that 5-10% of the population in Stockholm County were carrying the virus on 9 April.<ref Name=mellan5och10>{{cite web |last1=Zachrisson |first1=Lotta |title=Tegnell: \"Mellan fem och tio procent b\u00e4r p\u00e5 viruset\" |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/ny-studie-2-5-av-stockholmarna-bar-pa-viruset |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=sv |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government policy==\nThe [[Government of Sweden#Present Cabinet|Swedish government]] has tried to focus efforts on encouraging the right behaviour and creating social norms rather than mandatory restrictions. Government officials including [[Prime Minister of Sweden|Swedish prime minister]] [[Stefan L\u00f6fven]], as well as the [[Public Health Agency of Sweden]] have encouraged each individual to take responsibility for their own health and the health of others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dn.se/nyheter/sverige/ewa-stenberg-lofven-vill-hellre-overtyga-an-forbjuda/|title=Ewa Stenberg: L\u00f6fven vill hellre \u00f6vertyga \u00e4n f\u00f6rbjuda|date=27 March 2020|website=DN.SE|language=sv|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Swedish Constitution|Swedish constitution]] mandates that the relevant expert agency, in this case [[Public Health Agency of Sweden|the Public Health Agency]], must issue advice prior to any government actions aiming to prevent the spread of the virus with a strong mandate that the expert agencies should initiate actions, avoiding [[Ministerstyre|rule by ministers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gp.se/1.26081990|title=\"Vi epidemiologer har f\u00e5tt lite f\u00f6r stor makt\"|last=TT|date=2020-03-28|website=gp.se|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The independece of Swedish agencies and the choice of 'recommendations' instead of legislation has received much coverage in international media.<ref name=\"samtalet8aprilsida4\">{{cite web |title=Samtalet om Sverige 1\u20137 april 2020 |url=https://si.se/app/uploads/2020/04/samtalet-om-sverige-1-7-april-1.pdf |website=www.si.se |accessdate=14 April 2020 |page=4 |language=sv |date=8 April 2020}}</ref> Swedish [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Sweden)|foreign minister]], [[Ann Linde]] described Sweden as having \u2018rather small ministries, but rather big authorities\u2019 (with the Public Health Agency being one such authority), and this going back 300-400 years, and Sweden being characterized by a very high level of trust in its authorities from both the people and the politicians, and that Swedes had a very strong urge to following recommendations from authorities, thus making legislation largely unnecessary. When asked if Sweden would consider stronger restriction, L\u00f6fven and Linde has both made clear that the Swedish government wouldn't hesitate to do so if deemed necessary and on advice from the expert agencies, but that such measures needed to be taken at the right time, and that they believe it's hard do make people obey [[lockdown|lockdowns]] for an extended period.<ref name=\"lindecnn\">{{cite web |title=Ann Linde: \u201dFinns m\u00e5nga myter om svenska strategin\u201d |url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/ann-linde-finns-manga-myter-om-svenska-strategin/ |website=www.expressen.se |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=9359b030-704e-11ea-aa9a-936e6c4209ee&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAyMC0wMy0yMi9zd2VkZW4tcHJpbWUtbWluaXN0ZXItc2F5cy1wcmVwYXJlLWZvci1tb3JlLXJlc3RyaWN0aXZlLXBvbGljaWVz|title=Sweden Prime Minister Says Prepare for More Restrictive Policies|last=Rolander|first=Niclas|date=22 March 2020|website=bloomberg.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n\n[[File:FHM-Covid-19-Undvik-smitta-a4-engelska-raster.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|In response to COVID-19, the [[Public Health Agency of Sweden]] issued a series of infographics in different languages describing how to protect oneself and others from infection.]]<!--This image is specially made in response to COVID-19, and is general on purpose-->\n===Recommendations===\nOn 10 March, responding to indications of [[Transmission (medicine)#Definition and related terms|community transmission]], the [[Public Health Agency of Sweden|Public Health Agency]] advised everyone with respiratory infection, even mild ones, to refrain from social contacts where there is a risk of spreading the virus, in private as well as working life. They also ask health care staff working with risk groups, including nursing homes, not work if they have any symptoms of respiratory infection. Relatives of elderly should also avoid unnecessary visits at hospitals and in facilities for elderly, and never visit if there are any respiratory symptoms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/mars/flera-tecken-pa-samhallsspridning-av-covid-19-i-sverige/|title=Flera tecken p\u00e5 samh\u00e4llsspridning av covid-19 i Sverige \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se|language=sv|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Stefansson |first1=Klara |title=Risken f\u00f6r coronaspridning i Sverige h\u00f6js till \"mycket h\u00f6g\" |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/risken-for-coronaspridning-i-sverige-hojs-till-mycket-hog |website=SVT Nyheter |language=sv |date=10 March 2020}}</ref> On 16 March, the agency of Sweden recommended that people over 70 should limit close contact with other people, and employers should recommend their employees work from home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/mars/personer-over-70-bor-begransa-sociala-kontakter-tills-vidare/|title=Personer \u00f6ver 70 b\u00f6r begr\u00e4nsa sociala kontakter tills vidare \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se}}</ref> The following day, the agency recommended that secondary schools and universities use distance learning,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/mars/larosaten-och-gymnasieskolor-uppmanas-nu-att-bedriva-distansundervisning/|title=L\u00e4ros\u00e4ten och gymnasieskolor uppmanas nu att bedriva distansundervisning \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se}}</ref> with schools following suit all over the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.svd.se/presstraff-i-dag-med-utbildningsministern|title=L\u00f6fven: Gymnasier ska g\u00e5 \u00f6ver till distansstudier}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an analysis of mobile network data from the [[Easter|Easter week]] carried out by [[mobile network operator]] [[Telia]], most Swedes had followed the agency's recommendations to avoid unnecessary travels during the Easter holidays. Overall, travel from the Stockholm region had decreased by 80-90%, and the number of citizens of [[Stockholm]] travelling to popular holiday destinations like [[Gotland]] and the ski resorts in [[\u00c5re]] had fallen with more than 90%. Travel between other regions in Sweden had fallen as well.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stockholmare stannar hemma i p\u00e5sk |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/snabbkollen/stockholmare-stannar-hemma-i-pask |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=sv |date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Svenskarna stannar hemma under p\u00e5sklovet |url=http://press.telia.se/pressreleases/svenskarna-stannar-hemma-under-paasklovet-2990179 |website=Mynewsdesk |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=sv}}</ref> [[Ferry|Ferry-line]] operator [[Destination Gotland]], who previously had called on their customers to rethink their planned trips for Easter, reported that 85% of all bookings had been rescheduled.<ref>{{cite web |last1=S. Zetterdahl |first1=Christian |title=85 procent har bokat av p\u00e5skresan med Gotlandsf\u00e4rjan |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/ost/85-procent-har-bokat-av-resan-med-gotlandsfarjan |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=sv |date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Rules and legislation===\nOn 11 March, the same day as the first Swedish death to COVID-19, the Swedish government passed a new law, limiting [[freedom of assembly]] by temporarily banning all gatherings larger than 500 people, with threat of fine and prison.<ref name=\":34\">{{Cite news|last=V. Nyheter|first=S.|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/snabbkollen/regeringen-stoppar-stora-moten|title=Regeringen stoppar stora m\u00f6ten|date=11 March 2020|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=11 March 2020|language=sv}}</ref> The ban will apply until further notice.<ref name=\"Klart\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gp.se/nyheter/sverige/klart-inga-evenemang-med-fler-%C3%A4n-500-bes%C3%B6kare-1.25224161|title=Klart: Inga evenemang med fler \u00e4n 500 bes\u00f6kare|date=11 March 2020|website=gp.se|language=sv|trans-title=Clear: No events with more than 500 visitors}}</ref>\nOn 27 March the government announced that gatherings of more than 50 people were banned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.krisinformation.se/nyheter/2020/mars/ytterligare-begransning-sammankomster|title=F\u00f6rbud mot allm\u00e4nna sammankomster med fler \u00e4n 50 personer|date=2020-03-27|access-date=2020-03-28|language=sv}}</ref><ref name=\"SVD50people\">{{cite web |url=https://www.svd.se/stefan-lofven-och-rikspolischefen-haller-presstraff/ |title=Sammankomster p\u00e5 \u00f6ver 50 personer f\u00f6rbjuds |first1=Hanna| last1=Frejdeman |date=27 March 2020 |website= |publisher=SvD |access-date=27 March 2020 |quote= |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\nAgain, on the 11th of March, the karensdag, the unpaid first day of sick leave, was temporarily discontinued in an effort to encourage people to stay home if they were experiencing symptoms that are consistent with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.se/20200311/sweden-changes-sick-pay-rules-to-help-fight-coronavirus|title=Sweden Changes Sick Pay Rules to Help Fight CoronaVirus|last=|first=|date=|website=thelocal.se|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> On 13 March, the government decided to temporarily abolish the demand of a doctor's certificate for 14 days for people staying home from work due to illness (i.e. sick pay period). Previously a doctor's certificate was needed after seven days.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Olsson|first=Jonas|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/regeringen-kravet-pa-lakarintyg-vid-sjukdom-avskaffas|title=Regeringen: Kravet p\u00e5 sjukintyg avskaffas tillf\u00e4lligt|date=13 March 2020|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=13 March 2020|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, the government introduced new restrictions to bars and restaurants requiring all service to be table service only. Restaurants were also recommended increase the space between the tables. Venues that do not adhere to the new restrictions could be shut down.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Larsson|first=Ylva|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/nya-forbudet-endast-bordsservering-tillats-pa-restauranger-och-barer|title=Nya restriktioner: Endast bordsservering till\u00e5ts p\u00e5 restauranger och barer|date=2020-03-24|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=2020-03-27|language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/nya-forbudet-endast-bordsservering-tillats-pa-restauranger-och-barer|title=Nya restriktioner: Endast bordsservering till\u00e5ts p\u00e5 restauranger och barer|date=24 March 2020|language=sv|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBeginning on 1 April, all private visits to nursing homes was outlawed by the government. Many [[Municipality (Sweden)|municipalities]] had already forbidden such visits. The national ban was however general, and those in charge of the facilities would be able to make exceptions under special circumstances, provided that the risk of spread of the virus was low.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nationellt bes\u00f6ksf\u00f6rbud p\u00e5 \u00e4ldreboenden |url=https://www.lidkopingsnytt.nu/2020/03/31/nationellt-besoksforbud-pa-aldreboenden/ |website=Lidk\u00f6pingsnytt |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=sv |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Travel restrictions===\nThe government has issued progressively stricter advisories against travel. Beginning on 17 February, the [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (Sweden)|Swedish Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] advised against all trips to [[Hubei Province]], [[China]], as well as non-essential travel to the rest of [[China]] apart from [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macao]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regeringen.se/uds-reseinformation/ud-avrader/kina---avradan/|title=Kina - avr\u00e5dan|last=Regeringskansliet|first=Regeringen och|date=26 January 2020|website=Regeringskansliet|language=sv|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dn.se/nyheter/varlden/ud-stramar-at-rekommendationerna-for-resor-till-kina/|title=UD stramar \u00e5t rekommendationerna f\u00f6r resor till Kina|date=2020-02-17|website=DN.SE|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\nOn 2 March the Ministry for Foreign Affairs advised against trips to [[Iran]], due to the uncontrolled spread of the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|Covid-19]] in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regeringen.se/uds-reseinformation/ud-avrader/iran---avradan/|title=Iran - avr\u00e5dan|last=Regeringskansliet|first=Regeringen och|date=27 February 2020|website=Regeringskansliet|language=sv|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Swedish Transport Agency]] also revoked [[Iran Air]]'s permit for Iranian flights to land in Sweden from the same date.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Andersson|first=Jane|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/skane/inga-sarskilda-coronakontroller-pa-kastrup|title=Inga flyg med Iran Air till Kastrup|date=3 March 2020|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=15 March 2020|language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regeringen.se/uds-reseinformation/ud-avrader/iran---avradan/|title=Iran - avr\u00e5dan|last=Regeringskansliet|first=Regeringen och|date=2020-02-27|website=Regeringskansliet|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> According to the foreign ministry, there were several thousands Swedish citizens in Iran at the time of the ban, many of them with difficulties getting back to Sweden.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Param |first1=Babak |last2=Axelsson |first2=Staffan |title=Svenskar fast i Iran \u2013 \u201dIngen fr\u00e5n Sverige har s\u00f6kt mig\u201d |url=https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=83&artikel=7418320 |website=Sveriges Radio |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=sv}}</ref> On 6 March, the Ministry for Foreign Affairs advised against all non-necessary trips to northern [[Italy]], specifically the regions of [[Piedmont|Piemonte]], [[Liguria]], [[Lombardy|Lombardia]], [[Emilia-Romagna]], [[Trentino-Alto Adige/S\u00fcdtirol|Trentino-Alto Adige]], [[Aosta Valley|Valle d'Aosta]], [[Veneto]], [[Friuli Venezia Giulia]], [[Marche]] and [[Tuscany|Toscana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regeringen.se/uds-reseinformation/ud-avrader/italien---avradan/|title=Italien - avr\u00e5dan|last=Regeringskansliet|first=Regeringen och|date=6 March 2020|website=Regeringskansliet|language=sv|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> [[Turin]], [[Milan]], [[Venice]], [[Verona]], [[Trieste]] and [[Florence]] are large cities in these regions. The [[Public Health Agency of Sweden]], who initiated the recommendation for the Ministry for Foreign Affairs, states that the decision is based solely on the strain of the Italian health care system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/mars/folkhalsomyndigheten-har-rekommenderat-avradan-fran-resor-till-norra-italien/|title=Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten har rekommenderat avr\u00e5dan fr\u00e5n resor till norra Italien \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se|language=sv|access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref> On similar grounds, the foreign affairs ministry also advised against all non-necessary travel to the city of [[Daegu]] and the province of [[North Gyeongsang Province|Gyeongbuk]] in [[South Korea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regeringen.se/uds-reseinformation/ud-avrader/sydkorea---avradan/|title=Sydkorea - avr\u00e5dan|last=Regeringskansliet|first=Regeringen och|date=6 March 2020|website=Regeringskansliet|language=sv|access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref> The advice regarding travels to Italy was extended 10 March to include all of its regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regeringen.se/uds-reseinformation/ud-avrader/italien---avradan/|title=Italien - avr\u00e5dan|last=Regeringskansliet|first=Regeringen och|date=2020-03-10|website=Regeringskansliet|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Finally, all international travel was discouraged on 14 March. The advice was to be in place for one month, after which it would be up for review.<ref name=exceptionelltlage>{{cite web |last1=Karlsson |first1=Amanda |title=UD om strandade svenskarna: \"Exceptionellt l\u00e4ge\" |url=https://www.bohuslaningen.se/nyheter/v%C3%A4rlden/ud-om-strandade-svenskarna-exceptionellt-l%C3%A4ge-1.26027863 |website=bohuslaningen.se |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=sv |date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Makar|first=Maria|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/coronaviruset-ud-avrader-fran-icke-nodvandiga-resor-till-alla-lander|title=Coronaviruset \u2013 UD avr\u00e5der fr\u00e5n icke n\u00f6dv\u00e4ndiga resor till alla l\u00e4nder|date=2020-03-14|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=2020-03-27|language=sv}}</ref> Travel from non-[[European Union|EU]]/[[European Economic Area|EEA]] member states was stopped on 17 March<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regeringen.se/artiklar/2020/03/fragor-och-svar--inresestopp-till-eu-via-sverige/|title=Fr\u00e5gor och svar \u2013 inresef\u00f6rbud till EU via Sverige|last=Regeringskansliet|first=Regeringen och|date=2020-03-17|website=Regeringskansliet|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> and unnecessary travel within Sweden was advised against on 19 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.krisinformation.se/nyheter/2020/mars/tank-over-om-resan-ar-nodvandig|title=Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten: T\u00e4nk \u00f6ver om resan verkligen \u00e4r n\u00f6dv\u00e4ndig|website=krisinformation.se|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/mars/tank-over-om-resan-verkligen-ar-nodvandig|title=T\u00e4nk \u00f6ver om resan verkligen \u00e4r n\u00f6dvandig|date=19 March 2020|language=sv|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe foreign ministry estimated that between 40,000 and 60,000 Swedes were stranded abroad in late March.<ref name=exceptionelltlage /><ref name=tiotusentalsstrandadesvenskar>{{cite web |author1=Emma Bouvin |author2=Karin Eriksson |title=Tiotusentals strandade svenskar v\u00e4djar om hj\u00e4lp att komma hem - DN.SE |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328103701/https://www.dn.se/nyheter/sverige/tiotusentals-strandade-svenskar-vadjar-om-hjalp-att-komma-hem/ |website=web.archive.org |accessdate=12 April 2020 |date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, the foreign ministry extended the advice against all non-essential travel abroad until 15 June, when it would again be reconsidered.<ref>{{cite web |title=Utlandsresor \u2013 f\u00f6rl\u00e4ngd avr\u00e5dan fr\u00e5n icke n\u00f6dv\u00e4ndiga resor till alla l\u00e4nder |url=https://www.regeringen.se/pressmeddelanden/2020/04/utlandsresor--forlangd-avradan-fran-icke-nodvandiga-resor-till-alla-lander |website=Regeringskansliet och Regeringskansliet |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=sv |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Economics===\nIn mid-March, the government proposed a 300 billion [[Swedish krona|SEK]] (\u20ac27bn) emergency package to reduce the economic impact of the crisis. The proposal included a system with a reduction in [[working time|work hours]] where the government will pay half to salary, aiming to help businesses stay afloat without having to do layoffs. Further, the government would pay the employer's expenses for any [[sick leave]]s, which is normally shared between the employer and the state.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Liljestr\u00f6m |first1=Elias |url=https://www.thelocal.se/20200317/what-does-the-coronavirus-mean-for-swedish-economy |title=What does the coronavirus mean for the Swedish economy?|website=thelocal.se |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The normal costs of employer contributions have also been temporarily discontinued for small business owners. This will save small businesses approximately 5000 SEK per employee each month but will result in a loss of tax revenue of 33 billion SEK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dn.se/nyheter/sverige/nytt-krispaket-presenteras-av-regeringen/|title=Tillf\u00e4lligt slopad arbetsgivaravgift i nytt krispaket|date=25 March 2020|website=DN.SE|language=sv|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The budget emergency package proposed by the government in mid-March to lessen the economic impact of the crisis was supported across the political spectrum, including all parties in opposition in the [[Riksdag]]. It was also welcomed by [[trade union]]s as well as the private and business sectors. However, some union representatives stressed that 'it won't be enough', a view shared by the biggest [[employer's organisation]], the [[Confederation of Swedish Enterprise]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Larsson |first1=Thomas |title=Oppositionen sluter upp bakom regeringens st\u00f6dpaket |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/ekonomi/oppositionen-sluter-upp-bakom-regeringens-stodpaket |website=SVT Nyheter |language=sv |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nLocal governments, such as the [[G\u00e4vle kommun|municipal government in G\u00e4vle]], have applied measures to businesses delaying the payment of invoices until September 1, 2020 at the earliest and deferring rent payments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gavle.se/service-och-information/information-om-coronaviruset/foretag-och-naringsliv-gallande-coronaviruset/|title=F\u00f6retag och n\u00e4ringsliv \u2013 coronaviruset|work=G\u00e4vle kommun|access-date=2020-03-27|language=sv-SE}}</ref>\nOn 2 April, the [[Financial Supervisory Authority (Sweden)|Financial Supervisory Authority]] ('''Finansinspektionen''<nowiki/>') decided that Swedish banks temporarily can allow exemptions for housing mortgage lenders regarding amortizing of loans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fi.se/sv/publicerat/pressmeddelanden/2020/banker-far-ge-alla-bolanetagare-undantag-fran-amortering/|title=Banker f\u00e5r ge alla bol\u00e5netagare undantag fr\u00e5n amortering - Finansinspektionen|website=fi.se|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Response from the public healthcare system==\n\n===Testing===\nThe first tests were carried out in January, and according to the [[Swedish Public Health Agency]], \u2018around twenty tests\u2019 had already been carried out before the first positive case was confirmed on 30 January.<ref name=fhmpress200131 /> The agency considered that all individuals who developed any symptoms of disease in the respiratory tract after visiting [[Wuhan]] should be tested, even those with less severe symptoms.<ref name=\"annuingacoronafall\">{{cite web |last1=Cederberg |first1=Jesper |title=\u00c4nnu inga coronafall i Sverige |url=https://lakartidningen.se/Aktuellt/Nyheter/2020/01/Annu-inga-coronafall-i-Sverige/ |website=L\u00e4kartidningen |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=sv-SE |date=27 January 2020}}</ref> The Public Health Agency expanded testing for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|Covid-19]] on 4 March beyond only those who have been in risk areas abroad, to also test cases of pneumonia without known cause.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Thomsen|first=Dante|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/nu-ska-fler-svenskar-testas-for-coronavirus|title=Nu ska fler svenskar testas f\u00f6r coronavirus|date=4 March 2020|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=7 March 2020|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nInitially, all tests were carried out at the agency's [[Public Health Agency of Sweden#High-containment laboratory|high-containment laboratory]] in [[Solna]]. But in mid-February, in order to increase testing capacity and allow for faster test results, testing also began at the [[Medical laboratory|clinical medical laboratories]] in [[Sahlgrenska University Hospital|G\u00f6teborg]], [[Halmstad]], [[Sk\u00e5ne University Hospital|Lund]], [[Sk\u00f6vde]], [[Stockholm]], [[Norrland University Hospital|Ume\u00e5]] and [[University Hospital|Uppsala]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pramsten |first1=Sara |title=Fler labb f\u00e5r m\u00f6jlighet att analysera coronavirus |url=https://lakartidningen.se/Aktuellt/Nyheter/2020/02/Fler-labb-far-mojlighet-att-analysera-Coronavirus/# |website=L\u00e4kartidningen |publisher=L\u00e4kartidningen F\u00f6rlag AB |accessdate=12 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308211841/https://lakartidningen.se/Aktuellt/Nyheter/2020/02/Fler-labb-far-mojlighet-att-analysera-Coronavirus/ |archivedate=8 March 2020 |language=sv-SE |date=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nBetween 27 March and 3 April, the health agency tested approximately 800 randomly selected individuals in Stockholm County, to seek knowledge of the then current infection rate.<ref name=\"Resultat fr\u00e5n unders\u00f6kning av f\u00f6rek\">{{cite web |title=Resultat fr\u00e5n unders\u00f6kning av f\u00f6rekomsten av covid-19 i region Stockholm \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten |url=https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/april/resultat-fran-undersokning-av-forekomsten-av-covid-19-i-region-stockholm/ |website=www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=sv |format=Press release |date=9 April 2020}}</ref> \nAs it was estimated that Stockholm County by then had the highest infection rate in Sweden, the agency choose to focus on that region.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hansson |first1=Anna |title=Tester ska visa coronakurvan i Sverige |url=https://www.nyteknik.se/samhalle/tester-ska-visa-coronakurvan-i-sverige-6991681 |website=Ny Teknik |accessdate=10 April 2020 |language=sv |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> According to the results, 2.5% of the local population were carrying the virus in the upper respiratory tract during the surveyed period.<ref name=\"Resultat fr\u00e5n unders\u00f6kning av f\u00f6rek\"/>\nBased on the study and a [[doubling time]] of 6-7 days, the agency concluded that 5-10% of the population in the region were carrying the virus on 9 April.<ref Name=mellan5och10 />\n\nAt the end of March, the number of tests carried out each week numbered 10.000.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bergendorff |first1=Johan |title=Tegnell: Mer testning skulle skydda \u00e4ldre b\u00e4ttre |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/vetenskap/tegnell-mer-testning-skulle-skydda-aldre-battre |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=sv |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Capacity===\nThe [[Stockholm International Fairs]], Stockholmsm\u00e4ssan, are being converted into a field hospital with the help of the [[Swedish Army|Swedish Defence Forces]]. The field hospital will be able to house 600 seriously and critically sick patients.<ref name=\"stockholmsmassan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dn.se/sthlm/har-byggs-stockholmsmassan-om-till-sjukhus/|title=H\u00e4r byggs Stockholmsm\u00e4ssan om till sjukhus|date=2020-03-27|website=DN.SE|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The Swedish Defence Forces will provide equipment for 30 of the 600 beds and the [[Stockholm Regional Council]] will provide the remaining 570.<ref name=\"stockholmsmassan\"/> The facilities are used for treating less severe cases, as opposed to those needing [[Intensive care unit|intensive care]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bj\u00f6rk |first1=Frida |title=\u00d6verl\u00e4kare sl\u00e5r larm om t\u00e4ltet p\u00e5 \u00d6stra: \u201dRiskerar m\u00e4nniskors liv\u201d |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/vast/overlakare-slar-larm-om-taltet-pa-ostra-riskerar-manniskors-liv |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=sv |date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:\u00d6stra Sjukhuset COVID-19 F\u00e4ltsjukhus.jpg|thumb|An army-constructed [[field hospital]] outside [[Sahlgrenska University Hospital|\u00d6stra Sjukhuset]] in [[Gothenburg]] on 23 March 2020. The tents contain temporary [[intensive care unit]]<nowiki/>s for COVID-19 patients. ]]\n[[File:Coronat\u00e4ltet .jpg|thumb|Medical tent set up outside [[Visby]] Hospital, 14 March 2020.]]\n[[File:Sahlgrenska_Corona_20200229_142008.jpg|thumb|Streetsigns outside Sahlgrenska hospital from late February telling those with potential symptoms of COVID-19 to wait outside the hospital.]]\nThe increasing number of cases in large areas such as Stockholm and Uppsala has resulted in the cancellation or postponement of up to 90% of planned surgeries, including cancer related surgeries.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Carl\u00e9n|first=Linnea|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/nara-halften-av-alla-planerade-operationer-installda|title=N\u00e4ra h\u00e4lften av alla planerade operationer inst\u00e4llda|date=2020-03-27|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=2020-03-27|last2=Sima|first2=Lotta|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nBefore the pandemic, the Swedish healthcare system had the capacity to treat approximately 500 persons in [[Intensive Care Unit|intensive care units]] (ICU). The relatively low number of beds had stayed a source of concern as the crisis evolved, and even though the number had increased to 800 at the beginning of April, healthcare professionals continued to express worry that their hospitals would eventually run out of beds. According to the calculations of the Swedish health agency, up to 1300 ICU beds would be needed when Sweden reached the top of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olin |first1=Elisabet |title=Stor oro f\u00f6r kommande brist p\u00e5 intensivv\u00e5rdsplatser |url=https://lakartidningen.se/aktuellt/nyheter/2020/04/stor-oro-for-kommande-brist-pa-intensivvardsplatser/ |website=L\u00e4kartidningen}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Grill |first1=Marja |last2=Sima |first2=Lotta |last3=Velizelos |first3=Aris |last4=Ulander |first4=Kenneth |title=IVA-platserna sinar i landet \u2013 stor os\u00e4kerhet om de kommer att r\u00e4cka |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/iva-platserna-sinar-i-landet-stor-osakerhet-om-platserna-kreported(cka |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=2002-04-13|language=sv |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> On 13 April, the [[National Board of Health and Welfare (Sweden)|National Board of Health and Welfare]] reported that the total number of ICU beds had risen to 1039, with an occupancy of 80%.<ref>{{cite web |title=20 nya d\u00f6dsfall i Sverige |url=https://www.nsk.se/2020/04/13/20-nya-dodsfall-i-sverige/ |website=Norra Sk\u00e5ne |accessdate=13 April 2020|language=sv-SE}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Frejdeman |first1=Hannah |title=\u201dEfterrapportering att v\u00e4nta efter helgen\u201d |url=https://www.svd.se/just-nu-folkhalsomyndigheten-haller-presstraff |website=Svenska Dagbladet |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=sv |date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Equipment===\nOn 13 March, media reported that there is a shortage in [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE) for health care staff, and hospitals in Stockholm have been forced to reuse disposable PPEs after sanitation. The regional Health Care Director warned about this scenario in early March and government agencies have temporarily waived the public procurement law in order to hastily procure more supplies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/coronaviruset/vardforraden-borjar-sina-engangsskydd-ateranvands/|title=Sjukhusens f\u00f6rr\u00e5d b\u00f6rjar sina \u2013 eng\u00e5ngsskydd \u00e5teranv\u00e4nds i Stockholm|website=expressen.se|language=sv|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> The [[National Board of Health and Welfare (Sweden)|National Board of Health and Welfare]] ('''Socialstyrelsen''<nowiki/>') confirmed that there is no preparedness storage and nothing to distribute to the health care sector.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expressen.se/tv/nyheter/coronaviruset/socialstyrelsen-det-finns-ingenting-att-distribuera/|title=Covid-19: Brist p\u00e5 skyddsutrustning och provtagningsmaterial|website=Expressen TV|language=sv|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/a/lA5mAo|title=Larmet inifr\u00e5n v\u00e5rden: \"Finns ingen skyddsutrustning\"|website=Aftonbladet|language=sv|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Staffing===\nOn 25 March 2020, Bj\u00f6rn Eriksson, the Director of Healthcare in Stockholm, appealed to anyone in the [[Stockholm Regional Council|Stockholm region]] who had experience in healthcare to volunteer. As of the 26 March 2020, 5100 people with healthcare experience had registered as volunteers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dn.se/sthlm/over-5000-har-anmalt-sig-for-att-forstarka-varden-i-stockholm/|title=\u00d6ver 5.000 har anm\u00e4lt sig f\u00f6r att f\u00f6rst\u00e4rka v\u00e5rden i Stockholm|date=27 March 2020|website=DN.SE|language=sv|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe increasing number of cases in large areas such as Stockholm and Uppsala has resulted in the cancellation or postponement of up to 90% of planned surgeries, including cancer related surgeries.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Carl\u00e9n|first=Linnea|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/nara-halften-av-alla-planerade-operationer-installda|title=N\u00e4ra h\u00e4lften av alla planerade operationer inst\u00e4llda|date=2020-03-27|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=2020-03-27|last2=Sima|first2=Lotta|language=sv}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on society==\n===Transport===\nOn 15 March, [[Scandinavian Airlines|SAS]] announced that they would temporarily reduce their workforce by 10,000 people which constitutes roughly 90% of their workforce.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sasgroup.net/newsroom/press-releases/2020/sas-pausar-merparten-av-verksamheten/ |title=SAS pausar merparten av verksamheten |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=15 March 2020 |website= |publisher=SAS |access-date=27 March 2020 |quote= |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\nSoon almost every domestic flight were cancelled. Swedish authorities advised against all non-essential travel inside and out of Sweden. [[SAS Group|SAS]] decided to from 6 April 2020 fly only four domestic departures and four domestic arrivals from Arlanda, plus some international<ref>[https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/sas-fortsatter-trafikera-kiruna-och-lulea SAS beh\u00e5ller ett inrikesflyg \u2013 forts\u00e4tter trafikera fyra orter]</ref> while Norwegian cancelled all domestic flights in Sweden.<ref>[https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/norrbotten/norwegian-staller-in-alla-inrikesflyg Norwegian st\u00e4ller in alla inrikesflyg]</ref> Several airports closed altogether. Train routes were in general going with a more sparse schedule.\n\n===Education===\nOn 13 March 2020 the spring [[Swedish Scholastic Aptitude Test]] (''\u2032H\u00f6gskoleprovet\u2032''), was cancelled affecting approximately 70,000 prospective students who had registered themselves. This was the first time the Swedish Scholastic Aptitude Test has been cancelled since it was established in 1977.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Balcer Bednarska|first=Jaqueline|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/hogskoleprovet-3|title=H\u00f6gskoleprovet st\u00e4lls in \u2013 70 000 personer drabbas|date=2020-03-13|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=2020-03-27|language=sv}}</ref> On 23 March 2020 the [[National Agency for Education (Sweden)|Swedish National Agency for Education]] ('''Skolverket''<nowiki/>'), cancelled the [[Education in Sweden#National tests|national tests]] to give teachers in Sweden more time to prepare for the possibility of distance education.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skolverket.se/om-oss/press/pressmeddelanden/pressmeddelanden/2020-03-23-varens-nationella-prov-stalls-in|title=[2020-03-23] V\u00e5rens nationella prov st\u00e4lls in|website=skolverket.se|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n===Defence===\nThe [[Swedish Armed Forces]] cancelled the international [[military exercise]] Aurora 20 which was scheduled to be held between May and June. [[Austrian Armed Forces|Austria]] and [[Canadian Armed Forces|Canada]] had previously announced their cancellation of their planned participation.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olsson |first1=Jonas |title=Milit\u00e4r\u00f6vningen Aurora skjuts upp |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/militarovningen-aurora-skjuts-upp |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=sv |date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Politics===\nOn 25 March, The [[Swedish Social Democratic Party]] together with the [[Swedish Trade Union Confederation]] decided to cancel their traditional [[May Day|May Day demonstrations]]. They will instead hold an event on a digital platform, which will include speeches by the Swedish prime minister and leader of the Social Democrats, [[Stefan L\u00f6fven]], as well as union confederation leader [[Karl-Petter Thorwaldsson]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Yohannes |first1=Sofia |title=Socialdemokraternas 1 maj-t\u00e5g st\u00e4lls in |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/socialdemokraternas-1-maj-tag-stalls-in |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=sv |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Left Party (Sweden)]] also cancelled their nationwide demonstrations, and announced that there would instead be a digital celebration, including a speech by party leader [[Jonas Sj\u00f6stedt]].<ref>{{cite web |title=V\u00e4nsterpartiet anordnar digitalt f\u00f6rsta maj |url=https://www.etc.se/inrikes/vansterpartiet-anordnar-digitalt-forsta-maj |website=ETC |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=sv |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Almedalen Week]], considered to be the biggest and most important forum in Sweden for seminars, debates and political speeches on current social issues, held in [[Visby]] every summer,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wendt|first1=Maria|title=Almedalen \u2013 ett nationalromantiskt spektakel|trans-title=The Almedalen Week \u2013 a spectacle in the spirit of national romanticism|url=http://www.svd.se/kultur/understrecket/almedalen-ett-nationalromantiskt-spektakel_3711736.svd|website=svd.se|publisher=[[Svenska Dagbladet]]|date=6 July 2014|language=Swedish|accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> was cancelled as a result of the ban on large gatherings. The decision was taken on 1 April by the [[Gotland Municipality|organiser]] after consultation with the major political parties.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Johansson |first1=Sara |title=Almedalsveckan 2020 st\u00e4lls in |url=https://www.dagensjuridik.se/nyheter/almedalsveckan-2020-stalls-in/ |website=Dagens Juridik |publisher=Blendow Publishing AB |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=sv-SE |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Prime Minister Stefan L\u00f6fv\u00e9n had already announced that he had cancelled his planned participation in the upcoming event.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Larsson |first1=Carl |title=Statsministern avst\u00e5r Almedalen i sommar |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/ost/statsministern-avstar-almedalen-i-sommar |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=sv |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> A similar event in Stockholm, 'J\u00e4rvaveckan', was also cancelled, and won't be held until 2021.<ref>{{cite web |last1=R\u00e5gsj\u00f6 Thorell |first1=Andreas |title=J\u00e4rvaveckan flyttas fram till 2021 |url=https://www.resume.se/marknadsforing/sponsring-event/jarvaveckan-flyttas-fram-till-2021/ |website=www.resume.se |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=sv |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Culture===\nOn 6 March, Swedish National Broadcaster [[SVT]] held a crisis meeting to consider broadcasting the live finals of [[Melodifestivalen 2020]] on 7 March without an audience, as a response to the growing outbreak. The Danish equivalent had recently decided to broadcast [[Dansk Melodi Grand Prix|their version]] of the finals without an audience. Ultimately, SVT decided to allow the audience to enter the arena, although they advised people who felt sick to stay at home.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Laurell|first=Agnes|url=https://www.dn.se/kultur-noje/danska-melodifestivalen-framfors-utan-publik/|title=SVT inf\u00f6r Melodifestivalen: Stanna hemma om du k\u00e4nner dig sjuk|date=6 March 2020|work=DN|access-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=Lenas|first2=Sverker|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nStarting 30 March 2020 the public library in G\u00e4vle will start with a book delivery service for people aged 70 or older. The library will also start a take-away service where you can pre-loan books and pick them in a take-away bag.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gavle.se/omsorg-och-stod/gavle-bibliotek-infor-take-away-bokkasse-for-alla-och-hemleverans-av-bocker-for-riskgruppe/|title=G\u00e4vle bibliotek inf\u00f6r Take away-bokkasse f\u00f6r alla och hemleverans av b\u00f6cker f\u00f6r riskgrupper|work=G\u00e4vle kommun|access-date=27 March 2020|language=sv-SE}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nIn [[Sport of athletics|athletics]], all [[2020 Diamond League]] events scheduled to be held in May were postponed, which included the meet in [[Stockholm]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Diamond League i Stockholm uppskjutet |url=https://www.svt.se/sport/friidrott/diamond-league-i-stockholm-uppskjutet |website=SVT Sport |accessdate=5 April 2020 |language=sv |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The world's largest [[half marathon]] in Gothenburg, [[G\u00f6teborgsvarvet]], was postponed until later in 2020 and then cancelled completely on 27 March.<ref>{{cite web|author=Publicerad |url=https://www.svd.se/goteborgsvarvet-helt-installt-i-ar |title=G\u00f6teborgsvarvet helt inst\u00e4llt i \u00e5r &#124; SvD |publisher=Svd.se |date= |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref> The annual recreational [[road bicycle racing|bicycle race]] [[V\u00e4tternrundan]], scheduled to be held in June, was also cancelled as a result of the pandemic. The organisers made the decision public on 2 April.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Holmqvist |first1=Tobias |title=V\u00e4tternrundan 2020 st\u00e4lls in |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/ost/vatternrundan-2020-stalls-in|website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=2 April 2020 |date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Klart: V\u00e4tternrundan inst\u00e4lld |url=https://www.dn.se/sport/klart-vatternrundan-installd/ |website=DN.SE |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=sv |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, [[Swedish Football Association|the governing body for association football in Sweden]] formally announced that the premiere of the 2020 season for the first and second division leagues, men's [[Allsvenskan]] and [[Superettan]] as well as women's [[Damallsvenskan]] and [[Elitettan]], will be postponed to late May or early June. The decision will not affect the leagues below the second level.<ref>{{cite web |title=Klart: Allsvenskan skjuts upp |url=https://www.svt.se/sport/fotboll/klart-allsvenskan-stalls-in |website=SVT Sport |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=sv |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> Two days later it was announced that the 2020 edition of the association football award ceremony [[Fotbollsgalan]] was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Simon |first1=Bank |title=Sportbladet avsl\u00f6jar: Fotbollsgalan 2020 st\u00e4lls in |url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/sportbladet/fotboll/a/AdMegj/sportbladet-avslojar-fotbollsgalan-2020-stalls-in |website=Aftonbladet |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=sv |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> Many of the professional teams in the highest division warned that the loss of income following the postponement of the season would have a severe impact on their economy.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aronsson |first1=Claes |title=Allsvenska klubbarna planerar f\u00f6r katastrofl\u00e4ge - Radiosporten |url=https://sverigesradio.se/artikel/7434156 |website=sverigesradio.se |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=sv |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Professional [[handball]] was also affected, with the last rounds and the finals in the highest men's and women's leagues, [[Handbollsligan]] and [[Svensk handbollselit|Svensk handbollselit]], being cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Radio |first1=Sveriges |title=Svensk handboll st\u00e4ller in hela s\u00e4songen - Radiosporten |url=https://sverigesradio.se/artikel/7430818 |website=sverigesradio.se |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=sv |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> Similarly, the [[Swedish Basketball Federation]] choose to stop all games until May, effectively stopping the highest divisions [[Swedish Basketball League|SBL]] and [[Basketligan dam|SBL Dam]] mid-season.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Flink |first1=Johan |last2=Wahlberg |first2=Malin |title=St\u00e4ller in all basket resten av s\u00e4songen |url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/sportbladet/a/70GQbo/staller-in-all-basket-resten-av-sasongen |website=Aftonbladet |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=sv |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Speedway]], the start of [[Elitserien (speedway)|Elitserien]], the highest league in [[Speedway in Sweden|the Swedish league system]], was rescheduled to 2 June. In order to manage a tighter schedule, the [[Sports governing body|sport's governing body]] Swedish Motorcycle and Snowmobile Federation also decided to cancel the quarterfinals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Elitserien i speedway slopar kvartsfinalerna |url=https://ekuriren.se/sport/elitserien-i-speedway-slopar-kvartsfinalerna-sm5371664.aspx |website=ekuriren.se |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Debate==\nMany outside Sweden considered the Swedish policies and the measures taken by its [[Government of Sweden|government]] to fight the pandemic to be different when compared to most other countries. As a result, there was an increase in international news coverage of Sweden. Much of the coverage was neutral, but some of it also contained criticism.<ref name=\"samtalet8aprilsida5\">{{cite web |title=Samtalet om Sverige 1\u20137 april 2020 |url=https://si.se/app/uploads/2020/04/samtalet-om-sverige-1-7-april-1.pdf |website=www.si.se |accessdate=14 April 2020 |page=5 |language=sv |date=8 April 2020}}</ref> [[Global Times]], closely linked to the ruling [[Communist Party of China]], accused Sweden of having capitulated to the virus, calling the country 'a black hole' and called for the international community to condemn Sweden's actions.<ref name=\"kinakritiserar\">{{cite web |last1=Djurberg |first1=Bj\u00f6rn |title=Kina kritiserar Sveriges coronahantering |url=https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=83&artikel=7429175 |website=Sveriges Radio |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=sv |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Some, including Swedish [[Minister for Justice (Sweden)|justice minister]] [[Morgan Johansson]], speculated that the strong criticism may be partly linked to the [[China\u2013Sweden relations#Conflict over Gui Minhai|poor relations between the two countries]] after China's imprisonment of the Swedish book publisher [[Gui Minhai]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Foster |first1=Keith |title=China attacks Swedish virus response |url=https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=2054&artikel=7429323 |website=Radio Sweden |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=en |date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"kinakritiserar\" /> Many claimed the Sweden was pursuing a [[herd immunity|herd immunity strategy]],<ref name=\"samtalet8aprilsida5\" /> including [[President of the United States|US president]] [[Donald Trump]], who during a press briefing told the assembled media that Sweden was 'suffering very greatly' due to what he referred to as 'the herd', and that the US, if done the same, 'would have lost hundreds of thousands more people'.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sweden says Trump criticism of coronavirus strategy 'factually wrong' |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/europe/sweden-says-trump-criticism-of-coronavirus-strategy-factually-wrong |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en |date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/utrikes/trump-usa-hade-haft-tva-miljoner-doda-om-vi-foljt-sveriges-coronalinje |title=Trump: USA hade kanske haft tv\u00e5 miljoner d\u00f6da om vi f\u00f6ljt Sveriges coronalinje |publisher=SVT |author=Maria Makar|date=April 10, 2020|accessdate=April 13, 2020|lang=sv}}</ref> Responding partly to Trump's remarks, which she described by using the word \u2018misinformation\u2019, Swedish [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Sweden)|foreign minister]] [[Ann Linde]] said that the \u2018so-called Swedish strategy\u2019 was one of many myths about Sweden, and described it as \u2018absolutely false\u2019. Linde said that the Swedish goal was no different from most other countries; to save lives, hinder the spread of the virus and make the situation manageable for [[Healthcare in Sweden|the health system]].<ref name=\"lindecnn\" /> Sweden's chief [[epidemiology|epidemiologist]] [[Anders Tegnell]], when asked about Trump's remarks, said that in his opinion Sweden was doing relatively well, and were no worse off than [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/tegnell-om-trumps-utspel-jamfort-med-new-york-fungerar-det-bra-i-sverige |title=Tegnell om Trumps utspel: Man ska inte ta det p\u00e5 allvar |publisher=SVT |author=Prescilia Haddad|date=April 8, 2020|accessdate=April 13, 2020|lang=sv}}</ref> Many news stories in international media painted a picture of things being 'business as usual in Sweden, with its citizens ignoring the recommendations to practice [[social distancing]] and avoiding unnecessery travel.<ref name=\"samtalet8aprilsida5\" /> According to Linde, this was another of the myths in the reporting about Sweden, and she claimed Sweden's combination of recommendations and legally binding measures had so far proven effective.<ref name=\"lindecnn\" />\n\nWith Sweden having taken some of the least strict measures of any European country or of countries with a similar number of cases, the response has been both criticised and praised by international media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=b63abe70-704c-11ea-ba39-7b28c7fe6635&url=L29waW5pb24vYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAyMC0wMy0yNy9jb3JvbmF2aXJ1cy13YW50LXRvLWVzY2FwZS1hLWxvY2tkb3duLXRyeS1zd2VkZW4/c3JuZD1wcmVtaXVtLWV1cm9wZQ==|title=Want to Escape a Lockdown? Try Sweden \u2014 Do you trust millions of your fellow citizens to do the right thing in a pandemic?|last=Laurent|first=Lionel|date=27 March 2020|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=088c5a30-704d-11ea-a57a-3956084aed93&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAyMC0wMy0yMy9zd2VkZXMtdHJ5LWxhaXNzZXotZmFpcmUtbW9kZWwtaW4tY29udHJvdmVyc2lhbC12aXJ1cy1yZXNwb25zZQ==|title=Swedes Try Laissez-Faire Model in Controversial Virus Response|last=Rolander|first=Niclas|date=23 March 2020|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/31de03b8-6dbc-11ea-89df-41bea055720b|title=Sweden bucks global trend with experimental virus strategy {{!}} Free to read|last=Milne|first=Richard|date=25 March 2020|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 14th, a debate article was sent to Swedish newspapers signed by 22 academics, claiming that the strategy of the Swedish public health agency will lead to \"chaos in the healthcare system\". Moreover, they claimed that there is no transparency regarding the data used in the models made by the agency. [[Anders Tegnell]] from the public health agency responded to the criticism by saying that there is no lack in transparency in the agency's work and that all data is available to be downloaded by the public as an excel-file on their website. <ref>{{cite web |title=Ann Linde: \u201dForskare om Sveriges strategi: \u201dKommer att bli kaos\u201d\u201d |url=https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=83&artikel=7451820 |website=www.sverigesradio.se |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=sv}}</ref>  Additionally Tegnell stated that the numbers of deaths presented in the published article are wrong, especially regarding the specific number of deaths per day. Another claim in the article saying that Sweden's statistics are closing in on to the ones of Italy was countered by Anders Tegnell saying that unlike Sweden, Italy and many other countries only report on deaths in hospitals, making it hard to compare the numbers of the different countries. <ref>{{cite web |title=\"Tegnells svar p\u00e5 skarpa kritiken i DN-debatt: Grundl\u00e4ggande felaktigheter\" |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/forskare-kritiska-til-fhm-lat-politikerna-ta-over |website=www.svt.se |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=sv}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Sweden medical cases}}\n {{clear}}\n\n===Additional data===\nAs of 27 March, nearly 3 out of 4 patients in intensive care in Sweden were men. The majority of them had underlying symptoms such as high blood pressure. Also, a disproportionately high number of deaths among males was reported.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Larsson|first=Ylva|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/nastan-8-av-10-av-de-svarast-sjuka-i-sverige-ar-man|title=N\u00e4stan 3 av 4 av de som intensivv\u00e5rdats i Sverige \u00e4r m\u00e4n|date=26 March 2020|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=27 March 2020|last2=Andersson|first2=Ki|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nAt a point, it was reported that a disproportionate number of those that had died by then were Swedish Somali (6)<ref name=\"Randhawa\">{{Cite news|last=Randhawa|first=Rebecca|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/lakarforening-larmar-over-halften-av-de-doda-ar-svensksomalier|title=L\u00e4karf\u00f6rening larmar: Flera svensksomalier bland coronad\u00f6dsfall i Stockholmsomr\u00e5det|date=2020-03-23|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=2020-03-27|language=sv}}</ref>  out of 89<ref>{{cite web |title=30 mars: L\u00e4gesrapport om arbetet med det nya coronaviruset |url=https://www.sll.se/verksamhet/halsa-och-vard/nyheter-halsa-och-vard/2020/03/30-mars-lagesrapport-om-arbetet-med-det-nya-coronaviruset/ |website=Region Stockholm |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> deaths being members of the Swedish Somali community in the Stockholm region.<ref name=\"Randhawa\"/>\n\n====Charts====\n<small>\n'''Note:''' \nData is compiled by Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten at 11:30 (UTC+02:00) each day. Reports of new cases and deaths to Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten might be delayed by up to several days, especially around weekends, possibly introducing delays in reported number of cases for the last few days.<ref name=\"FHM_Aktuellt_l\u00e4ge\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/smittskydd-beredskap/utbrott/aktuella-utbrott/covid-19/aktuellt-epidemiologiskt-lage/|title=Bekr\u00e4ftade fall i Sverige \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|website=www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se|language=sv|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><br />\n</small>\n\n<!-- Leave OFF THE LAST DAY as its only a small part of data and will give the charts a false shape -->\n<!-- Do NOT ONLY update the last day, this will invalidate the graphs! Update at least the last 14 days, as data is backdated by source -->\n{{Image frame|caption={{small|{{right|source: FOHM<ref name=\"FHM_Official_stats\"/>}}}}{{Center|'''Total confirmed cases'''}}|pos=top|align=left|border=no|content=\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=720\n|linewidth=1\n|yGrid=|xGrid=\n|colors=#FF4500\n|xAxisAngle=-45\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|x=4 Feb, ., 26 Feb, 27 Feb, 28 Feb, 29 Feb, 1 Mar, 2 Mar, 3 Mar, 4 Mar, 5 Mar, 6 Mar, 7 Mar, 8 Mar, 9 Mar, 10 Mar, 11 Mar, 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 Mar, 15 Mar, 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr, 3 Apr, 4 Apr, 5 Apr, 6 Apr, 7 Apr, 8 Apr, 9 Apr, 10 Apr, 11 Apr, 12 Apr, 13 Apr, 14 Apr\n|yAxisMin=0|yAxisMax=12000\n|yAxisTitle=Cases\n|y=1, 1, 2, 3, 11, 14, 14, 19, 32, 61, 86, 146, 179, 225, 326, 424, 620, 771, 923, 994, 1063, 1146, 1265, 1410, 1553, 1733, 1867, 1984, 2166, 2396, 2710, 2996, 3362, 3662, 3943, 4357, 4832, 5318, 5873, 6476, 6833, 7174, 7565, 8304, 8960, 9604, 10056, 10445, 10898, 11318, 11758\n}}}}\n\n<!-- Leave OFF THE LAST DAY as its only a small part of data and will give the charts a false shape -->\n<!-- Do NOT ONLY update the last day, this will invalidate the graphs! Update at least the last 14 days, as data is backdated by source -->\n{{Image frame|caption={{small|{{right|source: FOHM<ref name=\"FHM_Official_stats\"/>}}}}{{Center|'''Cases per day'''}}|pos=top|align=center|b