{"title_page": "David Rolfe (Singer)", "text_new": "{{short description|American singer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = David Rolfe\n| birth_date         = November 23, (1968)<br>\nBrooklyn, New York, USA\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Singer\n| years_active       = 1998-present\n| spouse             = Tiffany Rolfe\n}}\n\n'''David Kos \"Music Man\" Rolfe''' (born November 23, 1968) is an American singer from [[New York City]] who has written and performed 5 English songs for the [[Pok\u00e9mon]] anime. Rolfe is currently working at [[advertising agency]] [[BBDO]] and is still continues to make music as of 2017.\n\n== Personal life ==\nDavid Rolfe was born in New York in November 23, 1968. He is married and has two children. Rolfe currently still lives in New York and still continues to make music as well as working at [[BBDO|BBDO New York]].\n\nRolfe wanted to be a producer, and even worked on a film in high school<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.myfirstshoot.com/interview/david-rolfe/|title=David Rolfe|website=My First Shoot|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref>. His first shoot was for an account called Truth which was the state of Florida anti tobacco initiative of the settlement.\n\n== Career ==\nDavid Rolfe is best known for performing five English opening for [[Pokemon]] and being the guitarist for the original Pok\u00e9mon [[Pok\u00e9mon Theme|Theme]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7453639/true-story-behind-pokemon-theme-song|title=Can't Regret Them All: The Story of the Very Lucrative 'Pokemon Theme'|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Pok\u00e9mon Theme|date=2020-01-15|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Pok%C3%A9mon_Theme&oldid=935935598|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> He was latter joined to sing the theme songs for Season [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Johto League Champions episodes|4]], [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Master Quest episodes|5]], [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Advanced episodes|6]], [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Advanced Challenge episodes|7]] and [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Advanced Battle episodes|8]]. He left the show when [[4Licensing Corporation|4Kids Entertainment]] lost the right to dub the [[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon Anime]] since he was working for 4Kids. Rolfe and John Siegler was not allowed to move to [https://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/TAJ_Productions Taj Production] and then replaced by [[John Loeffler]] (Who previously written most of the [[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]] Music).  Now Rolfe has a record label from [[Warner Chappell Music]] and still makes music. Right now he is working at [[BBDO]] as Director of Integrated Production. One of his recent music is [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EUJ7vluqtT0/ I'm History] released in 2018.\n\nDavid Rolfe has been credited for singing Born to be a Winner in the [[Pok\u00e9mon 4Ever|Fourth Pok\u00e9mon movie]], Believe in me in the [[Pok\u00e9mon Heroes|Fith Pok\u00e9mon movie]] and Unbeatable in the [[Pok\u00e9mon: Lucario and the Mystery of Mew|Eight Pok\u00e9mon movie]]. He also wrote the lyrics for You & Me & Pok\u00e9mon in [[Pokemon Heroes]] ending theme.\n\nRolfe spent much of his career at Crispin, Porter + Bogusky, as a partner and leader in CPB's forays into digital and innovation throughout the 2000s. Rolfe also ran Production at DDB Chicago for a short stint in 2006\u201307.\n\n== Awards ==\nOn the 16th May 2017, David Rolfe and Greg Hahn from [[BBDO|BBDO New York]] has won one [[Webby Award|21st Webby Award]] for agency of the year<ref>{{Citation|title=Greg Hahn and David Rolfe on the Red Carpet at the 21st Annual Webby Awards|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I8FCtrvp0y8|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=2017 Webby Awards|date=2020-01-17|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=2017_Webby_Awards&oldid=936284825|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\nDavid Rolfe has been credited for many films.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Films\n!Film Name\n!Year\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[The Skeleton Twins]]\n|2014\n|Writer: \"Life Is For Living\"\n|-\n|[[In the Beginning (2009 film)|In The Beginning]]\n|2009\n|Writer: \"Bus Stop Girl\" - As David Rolfe\n|-\n|[[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]]\n|1998\n|Writer / Singer: Born to be a Winner, Believe in Me, I Wanna Be a Hero, This Dream and Unbeatable. All co-written by David Rolfe and John Siegler\n|-\n|[[Pok\u00e9mon: Lucario and the Mystery of Mew]]\n|2005\n|Writer / Singer: Unbeatable. Co-written by David Rolfe and John Siegler\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Music\n!Music Name\n!Year\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]]\n|1998\n|Season 4\u20135, Guitarist for Season 1 (Not credited)\n|-\n|[[Pok\u00e9mon: Lucario and the Mystery of Mew]]\n|2005\n|Singer\n|-\n|[[Pok\u00e9mon Heroes]]\n|2002\n|Writer\n|}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.bbdo.nyc/people/ David Rolfe at BBDO New York]\n* [[imdbname:1344944|David Kos Rolfe at IMDb]]\n* [[bulba:David Rolfe|David Rolfe on Bulbapedia]]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EUJ7vluqtT0/ I'm History]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I8FCtrvp0y8 David Rolfe and Greg Hahn receiving the Webby Ward in 2017]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.w|ikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n\n{{Improve categories|date=February 2020}}\n\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rolfe, David}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American singer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = David Rolfe\n| birth_date         = November 23, (1968)<br>\nBrooklyn, New York, USA\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Singer\n| years_active       = 1998-present\n| spouse             = Tiffany Rolfe\n}}\n\n'''David Kos \"Music Man\" Rolfe''' (born November 23, 1968) is an American singer from [[New York City]] who has written and performed 5 English songs for the [[Pok\u00e9mon]] anime. Rolfe is currently working at [[advertising agency]] [[BBDO]] and is still continues to make music as of 2017.\n\n== Personal life ==\nDavid Rolfe was born in New York in November 23, 1968. He is married and has two children. Rolfe currently still lives in New York and still continues to make music as well as working at [[BBDO|BBDO New York]].\n\nRolfe wanted to be a producer, and even worked on a film in high school<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.myfirstshoot.com/interview/david-rolfe/|title=David Rolfe|website=My First Shoot|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref>. His first shoot was for an account called Truth which was the state of Florida anti tobacco initiative of the settlement.\n\n== Career ==\nDavid Rolfe is best known for performing five English opening for [[Pokemon]] and being the guitarist for the original Pok\u00e9mon [[Pok\u00e9mon Theme|Theme]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7453639/true-story-behind-pokemon-theme-song|title=Can't Regret Them All: The Story of the Very Lucrative 'Pokemon Theme'|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Pok\u00e9mon Theme|date=2020-01-15|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Pok%C3%A9mon_Theme&oldid=935935598|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> He was latter joined to sing the theme songs for Season [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Johto League Champions episodes|4]], [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Master Quest episodes|5]], [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Advanced episodes|6]], [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Advanced Challenge episodes|7]] and [[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Advanced Battle episodes|8]]. He left the show when [[4Licensing Corporation|4Kids Entertainment]] lost the right to dub the [[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon Anime]] since he was working for 4Kids. Rolfe and John Siegler was not allowed to move to [https://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/TAJ_Productions Taj Production] and then replaced by [[John Loeffler]] (Who previously written most of the [[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]] Music).  Now Rolfe has a record label from [[Warner Chappell Music]] and still makes music. Right now he is working at [[BBDO]] as Director of Integrated Production. One of his recent music is [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EUJ7vluqtT0/ I'm History] released in 2018.\n\nDavid Rolfe has been credited for singing Born to be a Winner in the [[Pok\u00e9mon 4Ever|Fourth Pok\u00e9mon movie]], Believe in me in the [[Pok\u00e9mon Heroes|Fith Pok\u00e9mon movie]] and Unbeatable in the [[Pok\u00e9mon: Lucario and the Mystery of Mew|Eight Pok\u00e9mon movie]]. He also wrote the lyrics for You & Me & Pok\u00e9mon in [[Pokemon Heroes]] ending theme.\n\nRolfe spent much of his career at Crispin, Porter + Bogusky, as a partner and leader in CPB's forays into digital and innovation throughout the 2000s. Rolfe also ran Production at DDB Chicago for a short stint in 2006\u201307.\n\n== Awards ==\nOn the 16th May 2017, David Rolfe and Greg Hahn from [[BBDO|BBDO New York]] has won one [[Webby Award|21st Webby Award]] for agency of the year<ref>{{Citation|title=Greg Hahn and David Rolfe on the Red Carpet at the 21st Annual Webby Awards|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I8FCtrvp0y8|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=2017 Webby Awards|date=2020-01-17|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=2017_Webby_Awards&oldid=936284825|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\nDavid Rolfe has been credited for many films.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Films\n!Film Name\n!Year\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[The Skeleton Twins]]\n|2014\n|Writer: \"Life Is For Living\"\n|-\n|[[In The Beginning]]\n|2009\n|Writer: \"Bus Stop Girl\" - As David Rolfe\n|-\n|[[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]]\n|1998\n|Writer / Singer: Born to be a Winner, Believe in Me, I Wanna Be a Hero, This Dream and Unbeatable. All co-written by David Rolfe and John Siegler\n|-\n|[[Pok\u00e9mon: Lucario and the Mystery of Mew]]\n|2005\n|Writer / Singer: Unbeatable. Co-written by David Rolfe and John Siegler\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Music\n!Music Name\n!Year\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]]\n|1998\n|Season 4\u20135, Guitarist for Season 1 (Not credited)\n|-\n|[[Pok\u00e9mon: Lucario and the Mystery of Mew]]\n|2005\n|Singer\n|-\n|[[Pok\u00e9mon Heroes]]\n|2002\n|Writer\n|}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.bbdo.nyc/people/ David Rolfe at BBDO New York]\n* [[imdbname:1344944|David Kos Rolfe at IMDb]]\n* [[bulba:David Rolfe|David Rolfe on Bulbapedia]]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EUJ7vluqtT0/ I'm History]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I8FCtrvp0y8 David Rolfe and Greg Hahn receiving the Webby Ward in 2017]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.w|ikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n\n{{Improve categories|date=February 2020}}\n\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rolfe, David}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toIn the Beginning(link changed toIn the Beginning (2009 film)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Rolfe_(Singer)"}
{"title_page": "Slobodna Bosna", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n'''''Slobodna Bosna''''' ({{IPA-sh|sl\u00f4bodna\u02d0 b\u00f4sna|bs}}; English: ''Free Bosnia'') was an investigative weekly news magazine based in [[Sarajevo]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigative magazine's office set on fire in Bosnia and Herzegovina|url=https://www.ifex.org/bosnia_and_herzegovina/2013/09/23/seemo_statement_on_bosnia/|work=IFEX|accessdate=20 September 2014|date=23 September 2013}}</ref> It was established in August 1995 as a print edition and in 2000 an online edition started to exist. The print edition was abolished in December 2015 and ''Slobodna Bosna'' now operates only as an [[online magazine]].\n\n==Profile==\n\n\nBefore transferring to online space, Slobodna Bosna was one of the loudest and articulate critics of political figures, criminals and [[corruption in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lupiga.com/vijesti/nakon-1-000-brojeva-i-20-godina-slobodne-bosne-kraj-ili-pravi-pocetak|title=NAKON 1.000 BROJEVA I 20 GODINA SLOBODNE BOSNE: Kraj ili pravi po\u010detak?|last=Lupiga|website=Lupiga|language=hr|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. The magazine's frequent investigations of corruption have led politicians to sue the editor-in-chief Senad Avdi\u0107. On 23 June 1999, Sarajevo Municipal Court sentenced Avdi\u0107 to a two-month suspended jail term on charges of criminal libel.<ref>{{cite web|author=Daniel Omeragic|title=Alispahic and Mehmetovic are Experts in Getting Rid of \"Paper Trail\"|url=http://www.ex-yupress.com/oslob/oslob52.html|work=Ex-Yupress|access-date=20 September 2014|date=1 July 1999|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107161302/http://www.ex-yupress.com/oslob/oslob52.html|archive-date=7 January 2009|df=}}</ref> This led to the [[Committee to Protect Journalists]] to condemn the conviction and sentencing of Senad Avdi\u0107 on criminal libel charges as a violation of all international norms of [[press freedom]].<ref>[http://www.cpj.org/protests/99ltrs/Bosnia28June99.html Bosna] ''CPJ''. 28 June 1999.</ref>\n\nBefore the changes in leadership of the rivalry magazine ''[[Dani (magazine)|Dani]]'' and the transition of ''Slobodna Bosna'' to online space, these two magazines were seen as two most competent journalistic investigative hubs in Bosnia and Herzegovina.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lupiga.com/vijesti/nakon-1-000-brojeva-i-20-godina-slobodne-bosne-kraj-ili-pravi-pocetak|title=NAKON 1.000 BROJEVA I 20 GODINA SLOBODNE BOSNE: Kraj ili pravi po\u010detak?|last=Lupiga|website=Lupiga|language=hr|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n\n{{Newspapers in Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n\n[[Category:Media in Sarajevo]]\n[[Category:News magazines]]\n[[Category:Weekly magazines]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1995]]\n[[Category:1995 establishments in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n'''''Slobodna Bosna''''' ({{IPA-sh|sl\u00f4bodna\u02d0 b\u00f4sna|bs}}; English: ''Free Bosnia'') was an investigative weekly news magazine based in [[Sarajevo]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigative magazine's office set on fire in Bosnia and Herzegovina|url=https://www.ifex.org/bosnia_and_herzegovina/2013/09/23/seemo_statement_on_bosnia/|work=IFEX|accessdate=20 September 2014|date=23 September 2013}}</ref> It was established in August 1995 as a print edition and in 2000 an online edition started to exist. The print edition was abolished in December 2015 and ''Slobodna Bosna'' now operates only as an [[online magazine]].\n\n==Profile==\nThe magazine's frequent investigations of corruption have led politicians to sue the editor-in-chief Senad Avdi\u0107. On 23 June 1999, Sarajevo Municipal Court sentenced Avdi\u0107 to a two-month suspended jail term on charges of criminal libel.<ref>{{cite web|author=Daniel Omeragic|title=Alispahic and Mehmetovic are Experts in Getting Rid of \"Paper Trail\"|url=http://www.ex-yupress.com/oslob/oslob52.html|work=Ex-Yupress|access-date=20 September 2014|date=1 July 1999|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107161302/http://www.ex-yupress.com/oslob/oslob52.html|archive-date=7 January 2009|df=}}</ref> This led to the [[Committee to Protect Journalists]] to condemn the conviction and sentencing of Senad Avdi\u0107 on criminal libel charges as a violation of all international norms of press freedom.<ref>[http://www.cpj.org/protests/99ltrs/Bosnia28June99.html Bosna] ''CPJ''. 28 June 1999.</ref>\n\nIt is alleged by the rival Bosnian newsmagazine, ''[[BH Dani]]'', that Senad Avdi\u0107 was an informer known as \u0160\u0107epo who worked for Serb secret police, where he established connections, which he exploited in his later editorial work. ''Slobodna Bosna'' became substantially unpopular among [[Bosniak]] community after its editor promoted a book by Dominik Ilija\u0161evi\u0107 Como, an ethnic Croat convicted of [[war crimes]] committed on Bosnian Muslim civilians in [[Kiseljak|Kiseljak municipality]] by Croat forces during the 1992\u201394 [[Croat\u2013Bosniak War]].<ref>[http://www.24sata.info/5656 Presuda Kantonalnog suda Zenica za zlo\u010dine hrvatskih snaga nad bo\u0161njakim civilima u Vare\u0161u, Kiseljaku, Stupnom Dolu] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070515133723/http://www.24sata.info/5656 |date=2007-05-15 }} ''24 Sata''.</ref>\n\nThe magazine has a strong [[secular]] stance.<ref>{{cite web|author=Davor Marko|title=Citizenship in Media Discourse in Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Montenegro, and Serbia|url=http://www.citsee.ed.ac.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/108916/380_citizenshipinmediadiscourseinbosniaandherzegovinacroatiamontenegroandserbia.pdf|work=European Research Council|accessdate=20 September 2014|format=Working papers|year=2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n\n{{Newspapers in Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n\n[[Category:Media in Sarajevo]]\n[[Category:News magazines]]\n[[Category:Weekly magazines]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1995]]\n[[Category:1995 establishments in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n", "name_user": "Gochuko33!", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slobodna_Bosna"}
